72# Note to developers: all of PySpark functions here take string as column names whenever possible. 

73# Namely, if columns are referred as arguments, they can always be both Column or string, 

74# even though there might be few exceptions for legacy or inevitable reasons. 

75# If you are fixing other language APIs together, also please note that Scala side is not the case 

76# since it requires making every single overridden definition.

79def _get_jvm_function(name: str, sc: SparkContext) -> Callable: 

80 """ 

81 Retrieves JVM function identified by name from 

82 Java gateway associated with sc. 

83 """ 

84 assert sc._jvm is not None 

85 return getattr(sc._jvm.functions, name) 

86 

87 

88def _invoke_function(name: str, *args: Any) -> Column: 

89 """ 

90 Invokes JVM function identified by name with args 

91 and wraps the result with :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`. 

92 """ 

93 assert SparkContext._active_spark_context is not None 

94 jf = _get_jvm_function(name, SparkContext._active_spark_context) 

95 return Column(jf(*args)) 

96 

97 

98def _invoke_function_over_columns(name: str, *cols: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

99 """ 

100 Invokes n-ary JVM function identified by name 

101 and wraps the result with :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`. 

102 """ 

103 return _invoke_function(name, *(_to_java_column(col) for col in cols)) 

104 

105 

106def _invoke_function_over_seq_of_columns(name: str, cols: "Iterable[ColumnOrName]") -> Column: 

107 """ 

108 Invokes unary JVM function identified by name with 

109 and wraps the result with :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`. 

110 """ 

111 sc = get_active_spark_context() 

112 return _invoke_function(name, _to_seq(sc, cols, _to_java_column)) 

113 

114 

115def _invoke_binary_math_function(name: str, col1: Any, col2: Any) -> Column: 

116 """ 

117 Invokes binary JVM math function identified by name 

118 and wraps the result with :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`. 

119 """ 

120 

121 # For legacy reasons, the arguments here can be implicitly converted into column 

122 cols = [ 

123 _to_java_column(c) if isinstance(c, (str, Column)) else _create_column_from_literal(c) 

124 for c in (col1, col2) 

125 ] 

126 return _invoke_function(name, *cols) 

127 

128 

129def _options_to_str(options: Optional[Dict[str, Any]] = None) -> Dict[str, Optional[str]]: 

130 if options: 

131 return {key: to_str(value) for (key, value) in options.items()} 

132 return {}

135@try_remote_functions 

136def lit(col: Any) -> Column: 

137 """ 

138 Creates a :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` of literal value. 

139 

140 .. versionadded:: 1.3.0 

141 

142 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

143 Supports Spark Connect. 

144 

145 Parameters 

146 ---------- 

147 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`, str, int, float, bool or list, NumPy literals or ndarray. 

148 the value to make it as a PySpark literal. If a column is passed, 

149 it returns the column as is. 

150 

151 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

152 Since 3.4.0, it supports the list type. 

153 

154 Returns 

155 ------- 

156 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

157 the literal instance. 

158 

159 Examples 

160 -------- 

161 >>> df = spark.range(1) 

162 >>> df.select(lit(5).alias('height'), df.id).show() 

163 +------+---+ 

164 |height| id| 

165 +------+---+ 

166 | 5| 0| 

167 +------+---+ 

168 

169 Create a literal from a list. 

170 

171 >>> spark.range(1).select(lit([1, 2, 3])).show() 

172 +--------------+ 

173 |array(1, 2, 3)| 

174 +--------------+ 

175 | [1, 2, 3]| 

176 +--------------+ 

177 """ 

178 if isinstance(col, Column): 

179 return col 

180 elif isinstance(col, list): 

181 if any(isinstance(c, Column) for c in col): 

182 raise PySparkValueError( 

183 error_class="COLUMN_IN_LIST", message_parameters={"func_name": "lit"} 

184 ) 

185 return array(*[lit(item) for item in col]) 

186 else: 

187 if has_numpy and isinstance(col, np.generic): 

188 dt = _from_numpy_type(col.dtype) 

189 if dt is not None: 

190 return _invoke_function("lit", col).astype(dt).alias(str(col)) 

191 return _invoke_function("lit", col) 

192 

193 

194@try_remote_functions 

195def col(col: str) -> Column: 

196 """ 

197 Returns a :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` based on the given column name. 

198 

199 .. versionadded:: 1.3.0 

200 

201 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

202 Supports Spark Connect. 

203 

204 Parameters 

205 ---------- 

206 col : str 

207 the name for the column 

208 

209 Returns 

210 ------- 

211 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

212 the corresponding column instance. 

213 

214 Examples 

215 -------- 

216 >>> col('x') 

217 Column<'x'> 

218 >>> column('x') 

219 Column<'x'> 

220 """ 

221 return _invoke_function("col", col) 

222 

223 

224column = col

227@try_remote_functions 

228def asc(col: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

229 """ 

230 Returns a sort expression based on the ascending order of the given column name. 

231 

232 .. versionadded:: 1.3.0 

233 

234 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

235 Supports Spark Connect. 

236 

237 Parameters 

238 ---------- 

239 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

240 target column to sort by in the ascending order. 

241 

242 Returns 

243 ------- 

244 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

245 the column specifying the order. 

246 

247 Examples 

248 -------- 

249 Sort by the column 'id' in the descending order. 

250 

251 >>> df = spark.range(5) 

252 >>> df = df.sort(desc("id")) 

253 >>> df.show() 

254 +---+ 

255 | id| 

256 +---+ 

257 | 4| 

258 | 3| 

259 | 2| 

260 | 1| 

261 | 0| 

262 +---+ 

263 

264 Sort by the column 'id' in the ascending order. 

265 

266 >>> df.orderBy(asc("id")).show() 

267 +---+ 

268 | id| 

269 +---+ 

270 | 0| 

271 | 1| 

272 | 2| 

273 | 3| 

274 | 4| 

275 +---+ 

276 """ 

277 return col.asc() if isinstance(col, Column) else _invoke_function("asc", col)

789@try_remote_functions 

790def product(col: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

791 """ 

792 Aggregate function: returns the product of the values in a group. 

793 

794 .. versionadded:: 3.2.0 

795 

796 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

797 Supports Spark Connect. 

798 

799 Parameters 

800 ---------- 

801 col : str, :class:`Column` 

802 column containing values to be multiplied together 

803 

804 Returns 

805 ------- 

806 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

807 the column for computed results. 

808 

809 Examples 

810 -------- 

811 >>> df = spark.range(1, 10).toDF('x').withColumn('mod3', col('x') % 3) 

812 >>> prods = df.groupBy('mod3').agg(product('x').alias('product')) 

813 >>> prods.orderBy('mod3').show() 

814 +----+-------+ 

815 |mod3|product| 

816 +----+-------+ 

817 | 0| 162.0| 

818 | 1| 28.0| 

819 | 2| 80.0| 

820 +----+-------+ 

821 """ 

822 return _invoke_function_over_columns("product", col)

2377 divisor : str, :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or float 

2378 the column that contains divisor, or the specified divisor value 

2379 

2380 Returns 

2381 ------- 

2382 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

2383 positive value of dividend mod divisor. 

2384 

2385 Examples 

2386 -------- 

2387 >>> from pyspark.sql.functions import pmod 

2388 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([ 

2389 ... (1.0, float('nan')), (float('nan'), 2.0), (10.0, 3.0), 

2390 ... (float('nan'), float('nan')), (-3.0, 4.0), (-10.0, 3.0), 

2391 ... (-5.0, -6.0), (7.0, -8.0), (1.0, 2.0)], 

2392 ... ("a", "b")) 

2393 >>> df.select(pmod("a", "b")).show() 

2394 +----------+ 

2395 |pmod(a, b)| 

2396 +----------+ 

2397 | NaN| 

2398 | NaN| 

2399 | 1.0| 

2400 | NaN| 

2401 | 1.0| 

2402 | 2.0| 

2403 | -5.0| 

2404 | 7.0| 

2405 | 1.0| 

2406 +----------+ 

2407 """ 

2408 return _invoke_binary_math_function("pmod", dividend, divisor)

2443@try_remote_functions 

2444def dense_rank() -> Column: 

2445 """ 

2446 Window function: returns the rank of rows within a window partition, without any gaps. 

2447 

2448 The difference between rank and dense_rank is that dense_rank leaves no gaps in ranking 

2449 sequence when there are ties. That is, if you were ranking a competition using dense_rank 

2450 and had three people tie for second place, you would say that all three were in second 

2451 place and that the next person came in third. Rank would give me sequential numbers, making 

2452 the person that came in third place (after the ties) would register as coming in fifth. 

2453 

2454 This is equivalent to the DENSE_RANK function in SQL. 

2455 

2456 .. versionadded:: 1.6.0 

2457 

2458 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

2459 Supports Spark Connect. 

2460 

2461 Returns 

2462 ------- 

2463 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

2464 the column for calculating ranks. 

2465 

2466 Examples 

2467 -------- 

2468 >>> from pyspark.sql import Window, types 

2469 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([1, 1, 2, 3, 3, 4], types.IntegerType()) 

2470 >>> w = Window.orderBy("value") 

2471 >>> df.withColumn("drank", dense_rank().over(w)).show() 

2472 +-----+-----+ 

2473 |value|drank| 

2474 +-----+-----+ 

2475 | 1| 1| 

2476 | 1| 1| 

2477 | 2| 2| 

2478 | 3| 3| 

2479 | 3| 3| 

2480 | 4| 4| 

2481 +-----+-----+ 

2482 """ 

2483 return _invoke_function("dense_rank") 

2484

2489 Window function: returns the rank of rows within a window partition. 

2490 

2491 The difference between rank and dense_rank is that dense_rank leaves no gaps in ranking 

2492 sequence when there are ties. That is, if you were ranking a competition using dense_rank 

2493 and had three people tie for second place, you would say that all three were in second 

2494 place and that the next person came in third. Rank would give me sequential numbers, making 

2495 the person that came in third place (after the ties) would register as coming in fifth. 

2496 

2497 This is equivalent to the RANK function in SQL.

2500

2655@try_remote_functions 

2656def broadcast(df: DataFrame) -> DataFrame: 

2657 """ 

2658 Marks a DataFrame as small enough for use in broadcast joins. 

2659 

2660 .. versionadded:: 1.6.0 

2661 

2662 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

2663 Supports Spark Connect. 

2664 

2665 Returns

2668 DataFrame marked as ready for broadcast join. 

2669 

2670 Examples 

2671 -------- 

2672 >>> from pyspark.sql import types 

2673 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([1, 2, 3, 3, 4], types.IntegerType()) 

2674 >>> df_small = spark.range(3)

2677 +-----+---+

2680 | 1| 1| 

2681 | 2| 2| 

2682 +-----+---+

2685 sc = get_active_spark_context() 

2686 return DataFrame(cast(JVMView, sc._jvm).functions.broadcast(df._jdf), df.sparkSession)

2860

2862 Supports Spark Connect.

2869 other columns to compute on.

2873 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

2874 distinct values of these two column values. 

2875 

2876 Examples 

2877 --------

2879 >>> df1 = spark.createDataFrame([1, 1, 3], types.IntegerType())

2893 +----------------------------+ 

2894 |count(DISTINCT value, value)| 

2895 +----------------------------+ 

2896 | 4| 

2897 +----------------------------+ 

2898 """

2901 "count_distinct", _to_java_column(col), _to_seq(sc, cols, _to_java_column)

2905@try_remote_functions 

2906def first(col: "ColumnOrName", ignorenulls: bool = False) -> Column: 

2907 """Aggregate function: returns the first value in a group. 

2908 

2909 The function by default returns the first values it sees. It will return the first non-null 

2910 value it sees when ignoreNulls is set to true. If all values are null, then null is returned. 

2911 

2912 .. versionadded:: 1.3.0 

2913 

2914 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

2915 Supports Spark Connect. 

2916 

2917 Notes 

2918 ----- 

2919 The function is non-deterministic because its results depends on the order of the 

2920 rows which may be non-deterministic after a shuffle. 

2921 

2922 Parameters 

2923 ---------- 

2924 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

2925 column to fetch first value for. 

2926 ignorenulls : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

2927 if first value is null then look for first non-null value. 

2928 

2929 Returns 

2930 ------- 

2931 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

2932 first value of the group. 

2933 

2934 Examples 

2935 -------- 

2936 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([("Alice", 2), ("Bob", 5), ("Alice", None)], ("name", "age")) 

2937 >>> df = df.orderBy(df.age) 

2938 >>> df.groupby("name").agg(first("age")).orderBy("name").show() 

2939 +-----+----------+ 

2940 | name|first(age)| 

2941 +-----+----------+ 

2942 |Alice| null| 

2943 | Bob| 5| 

2944 +-----+----------+ 

2945 

2946 Now, to ignore any nulls we needs to set ``ignorenulls`` to `True` 

2947 

2948 >>> df.groupby("name").agg(first("age", ignorenulls=True)).orderBy("name").show() 

2949 +-----+----------+ 

2950 | name|first(age)| 

2951 +-----+----------+ 

2952 |Alice| 2| 

2953 | Bob| 5| 

2954 +-----+----------+ 

2955 """ 

2956 return _invoke_function("first", _to_java_column(col), ignorenulls) 

2957 

2958 

2959@try_remote_functions 

2960def grouping(col: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

2961 """ 

2962 Aggregate function: indicates whether a specified column in a GROUP BY list is aggregated 

2963 or not, returns 1 for aggregated or 0 for not aggregated in the result set. 

2964 

2965 .. versionadded:: 2.0.0 

2966 

2967 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

2968 Supports Spark Connect. 

2969 

2970 Parameters 

2971 ---------- 

2972 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

2973 column to check if it's aggregated. 

2974 

2975 Returns 

2976 ------- 

2977 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

2978 returns 1 for aggregated or 0 for not aggregated in the result set. 

2979 

2980 Examples 

2981 -------- 

2982 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([("Alice", 2), ("Bob", 5)], ("name", "age")) 

2983 >>> df.cube("name").agg(grouping("name"), sum("age")).orderBy("name").show() 

2984 +-----+--------------+--------+ 

2985 | name|grouping(name)|sum(age)| 

2986 +-----+--------------+--------+ 

2987 | null| 1| 7| 

2988 |Alice| 0| 2| 

2989 | Bob| 0| 5| 

2990 +-----+--------------+--------+ 

2991 """ 

2992 return _invoke_function_over_columns("grouping", col)

2995@try_remote_functions 

2996def grouping_id(*cols: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

2997 """ 

2998 Aggregate function: returns the level of grouping, equals to 

2999 

3000 (grouping(c1) << (n-1)) + (grouping(c2) << (n-2)) + ... + grouping(cn) 

3001 

3002 .. versionadded:: 2.0.0 

3003 

3004 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

3005 Supports Spark Connect. 

3006 

3007 Notes 

3008 ----- 

3009 The list of columns should match with grouping columns exactly, or empty (means all 

3010 the grouping columns). 

3011 

3012 Parameters 

3013 ---------- 

3014 cols : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

3015 columns to check for. 

3016 

3017 Returns 

3018 ------- 

3019 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

3020 returns level of the grouping it relates to. 

3021 

3022 Examples 

3023 -------- 

3024 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(1, "a", "a"), 

3025 ... (3, "a", "a"), 

3026 ... (4, "b", "c")], ["c1", "c2", "c3"]) 

3027 >>> df.cube("c2", "c3").agg(grouping_id(), sum("c1")).orderBy("c2", "c3").show() 

3028 +----+----+-------------+-------+ 

3029 | c2| c3|grouping_id()|sum(c1)| 

3030 +----+----+-------------+-------+ 

3031 |null|null| 3| 8| 

3032 |null| a| 2| 4| 

3033 |null| c| 2| 4| 

3034 | a|null| 1| 4| 

3035 | a| a| 0| 4| 

3036 | b|null| 1| 4| 

3037 | b| c| 0| 4| 

3038 +----+----+-------------+-------+ 

3039 """ 

3040 return _invoke_function_over_seq_of_columns("grouping_id", cols)

3043@try_remote_functions 

3044def input_file_name() -> Column: 

3045 """ 

3046 Creates a string column for the file name of the current Spark task. 

3047

3135@try_remote_functions 

3136def last(col: "ColumnOrName", ignorenulls: bool = False) -> Column: 

3137 """Aggregate function: returns the last value in a group. 

3138 

3139 The function by default returns the last values it sees. It will return the last non-null 

3140 value it sees when ignoreNulls is set to true. If all values are null, then null is returned. 

3141 

3142 .. versionadded:: 1.3.0 

3143 

3144 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

3145 Supports Spark Connect. 

3146 

3147 Notes 

3148 ----- 

3149 The function is non-deterministic because its results depends on the order of the 

3150 rows which may be non-deterministic after a shuffle. 

3151 

3152 Parameters 

3153 ---------- 

3154 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

3155 column to fetch last value for. 

3156 ignorenulls : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

3157 if last value is null then look for non-null value. 

3158 

3159 Returns 

3160 ------- 

3161 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

3162 last value of the group. 

3163 

3164 Examples 

3165 -------- 

3166 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([("Alice", 2), ("Bob", 5), ("Alice", None)], ("name", "age")) 

3167 >>> df = df.orderBy(df.age.desc()) 

3168 >>> df.groupby("name").agg(last("age")).orderBy("name").show() 

3169 +-----+---------+ 

3170 | name|last(age)| 

3171 +-----+---------+ 

3172 |Alice| null| 

3173 | Bob| 5| 

3174 +-----+---------+ 

3175 

3176 Now, to ignore any nulls we needs to set ``ignorenulls`` to `True` 

3177 

3178 >>> df.groupby("name").agg(last("age", ignorenulls=True)).orderBy("name").show() 

3179 +-----+---------+ 

3180 | name|last(age)| 

3181 +-----+---------+ 

3182 |Alice| 2| 

3183 | Bob| 5| 

3184 +-----+---------+ 

3185 """ 

3186 return _invoke_function("last", _to_java_column(col), ignorenulls) 

3187 

3188 

3189@try_remote_functions 

3190def monotonically_increasing_id() -> Column: 

3191 """A column that generates monotonically increasing 64-bit integers. 

3192 

3193 The generated ID is guaranteed to be monotonically increasing and unique, but not consecutive. 

3194 The current implementation puts the partition ID in the upper 31 bits, and the record number 

3195 within each partition in the lower 33 bits. The assumption is that the data frame has 

3196 less than 1 billion partitions, and each partition has less than 8 billion records. 

3197 

3198 .. versionadded:: 1.6.0 

3199 

3200 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

3201 Supports Spark Connect. 

3202 

3203 Notes 

3204 ----- 

3205 The function is non-deterministic because its result depends on partition IDs. 

3206 

3207 As an example, consider a :class:`DataFrame` with two partitions, each with 3 records. 

3208 This expression would return the following IDs: 

3209 0, 1, 2, 8589934592 (1L << 33), 8589934593, 8589934594. 

3210 

3211 Returns 

3212 ------- 

3213 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

3214 last value of the group. 

3215 

3216 Examples 

3217 -------- 

3218 >>> df0 = sc.parallelize(range(2), 2).mapPartitions(lambda x: [(1,), (2,), (3,)]).toDF(['col1']) 

3219 >>> df0.select(monotonically_increasing_id().alias('id')).collect() 

3220 [Row(id=0), Row(id=1), Row(id=2), Row(id=8589934592), Row(id=8589934593), Row(id=8589934594)] 

3221 """ 

3222 return _invoke_function("monotonically_increasing_id")

3257@try_remote_functions 

3258def percentile_approx( 

3259 col: "ColumnOrName", 

3260 percentage: Union[Column, float, List[float], Tuple[float]], 

3261 accuracy: Union[Column, float] = 10000, 

3262) -> Column: 

3263 """Returns the approximate `percentile` of the numeric column `col` which is the smallest value 

3264 in the ordered `col` values (sorted from least to greatest) such that no more than `percentage` 

3265 of `col` values is less than the value or equal to that value. 

3266 

3267 

3268 .. versionadded:: 3.1.0 

3269 

3270 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

3271 Supports Spark Connect. 

3272 

3273 Parameters 

3274 ---------- 

3275 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

3276 input column. 

3277 percentage : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`, float, list of floats or tuple of floats 

3278 percentage in decimal (must be between 0.0 and 1.0). 

3279 When percentage is an array, each value of the percentage array must be between 0.0 and 1.0. 

3280 In this case, returns the approximate percentile array of column col 

3281 at the given percentage array. 

3282 accuracy : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or float 

3283 is a positive numeric literal which controls approximation accuracy 

3284 at the cost of memory. Higher value of accuracy yields better accuracy, 

3285 1.0/accuracy is the relative error of the approximation. (default: 10000). 

3286 

3287 Returns 

3288 ------- 

3289 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

3290 approximate `percentile` of the numeric column. 

3291 

3292 Examples 

3293 -------- 

3294 >>> key = (col("id") % 3).alias("key") 

3295 >>> value = (randn(42) + key * 10).alias("value") 

3296 >>> df = spark.range(0, 1000, 1, 1).select(key, value) 

3297 >>> df.select( 

3298 ... percentile_approx("value", [0.25, 0.5, 0.75], 1000000).alias("quantiles") 

3299 ... ).printSchema() 

3300 root 

3301 |-- quantiles: array (nullable = true) 

3302 | |-- element: double (containsNull = false) 

3303 

3304 >>> df.groupBy("key").agg( 

3305 ... percentile_approx("value", 0.5, lit(1000000)).alias("median") 

3306 ... ).printSchema() 

3307 root 

3308 |-- key: long (nullable = true) 

3309 |-- median: double (nullable = true) 

3310 """ 

3311 sc = get_active_spark_context() 

3312 

3313 if isinstance(percentage, (list, tuple)): 

3314 # A local list 

3315 percentage = _invoke_function( 

3316 "array", _to_seq(sc, [_create_column_from_literal(x) for x in percentage]) 

3317 )._jc 

3318 elif isinstance(percentage, Column): 

3319 # Already a Column 

3320 percentage = _to_java_column(percentage) 

3321 else: 

3322 # Probably scalar 

3323 percentage = _create_column_from_literal(percentage) 

3324 

3325 accuracy = ( 

3326 _to_java_column(accuracy) 

3327 if isinstance(accuracy, Column) 

3328 else _create_column_from_literal(accuracy) 

3329 ) 

3330 

3331 return _invoke_function("percentile_approx", _to_java_column(col), percentage, accuracy) 

3332 

3333

3718@try_remote_functions 

3719def greatest(*cols: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

3720 """ 

3721 Returns the greatest value of the list of column names, skipping null values. 

3722 This function takes at least 2 parameters. It will return null if all parameters are null. 

3723 

3724 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

3725 

3726 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

3727 Supports Spark Connect. 

3728 

3729 Parameters

3736 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

3737 gratest value.

3742 >>> df.select(greatest(df.a, df.b, df.c).alias("greatest")).collect()

3745 if len(cols) < 2:

3788@try_remote_functions 

3789def when(condition: Column, value: Any) -> Column: 

3790 """Evaluates a list of conditions and returns one of multiple possible result expressions. 

3791 If :func:`pyspark.sql.Column.otherwise` is not invoked, None is returned for unmatched 

3792 conditions. 

3793 

3794 .. versionadded:: 1.4.0 

3795 

3796 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

3797 Supports Spark Connect. 

3798 

3799 Parameters 

3800 ---------- 

3801 condition : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

3802 a boolean :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` expression. 

3803 value : 

3804 a literal value, or a :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` expression. 

3805 

3806 Returns 

3807 ------- 

3808 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

3809 column representing when expression. 

3810 

3811 Examples 

3812 -------- 

3813 >>> df = spark.range(3) 

3814 >>> df.select(when(df['id'] == 2, 3).otherwise(4).alias("age")).show() 

3815 +---+ 

3816 |age| 

3817 +---+ 

3818 | 4| 

3819 | 4| 

3820 | 3| 

3821 +---+ 

3822 

3823 >>> df.select(when(df.id == 2, df.id + 1).alias("age")).show() 

3824 +----+ 

3825 | age| 

3826 +----+ 

3827 |null| 

3828 |null| 

3829 | 3| 

3830 +----+ 

3831 """ 

3832 # Explicitly not using ColumnOrName type here to make reading condition less opaque 

3833 if not isinstance(condition, Column): 

3834 raise PySparkTypeError( 

3835 error_class="NOT_COLUMN", 

3836 message_parameters={"arg_name": "condition", "arg_type": type(condition).__name__}, 

3837 ) 

3838 v = value._jc if isinstance(value, Column) else value 

3839 

3840 return _invoke_function("when", condition._jc, v)

3853@try_remote_functions 

3854def log(arg1: Union["ColumnOrName", float], arg2: Optional["ColumnOrName"] = None) -> Column: 

3855 """Returns the first argument-based logarithm of the second argument. 

3856 

3857 If there is only one argument, then this takes the natural logarithm of the argument. 

3858 

3859 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

3860 

3861 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

3862 Supports Spark Connect. 

3863 

3864 Parameters 

3865 ---------- 

3866 arg1 : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`, str or float 

3867 base number or actual number (in this case base is `e`) 

3868 arg2 : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`, str or float 

3869 number to calculate logariphm for. 

3870 

3871 Returns 

3872 ------- 

3873 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

3874 logariphm of given value. 

3875 

3876 Examples 

3877 -------- 

3878 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([10, 100, 1000], "INT") 

3879 >>> df.select(log(10.0, df.value).alias('ten')).show() # doctest: +SKIP 

3880 +---+ 

3881 |ten| 

3882 +---+

3884 |2.0| 

3885 |3.0| 

3886 +---+ 

3887 

3888 And Natural logarithm 

3889 

3890 >>> df.select(log(df.value)).show() # doctest: +SKIP 

3891 +-----------------+ 

3892 | ln(value)| 

3893 +-----------------+ 

3894 |2.302585092994046| 

3895 |4.605170185988092| 

3896 |4.605170185988092| 

3897 +-----------------+ 

3898 """ 

3899 if arg2 is None: 

3900 return _invoke_function_over_columns("log", cast("ColumnOrName", arg1)) 

3901 else: 

3902 return _invoke_function("log", arg1, _to_java_column(arg2))

4002@try_remote_functions 

4003def lag(col: "ColumnOrName", offset: int = 1, default: Optional[Any] = None) -> Column: 

4004 """ 

4005 Window function: returns the value that is `offset` rows before the current row, and 

4006 `default` if there is less than `offset` rows before the current row. For example, 

4007 an `offset` of one will return the previous row at any given point in the window partition. 

4008 

4009 This is equivalent to the LAG function in SQL. 

4010 

4011 .. versionadded:: 1.4.0 

4012 

4013 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

4014 Supports Spark Connect. 

4015 

4016 Parameters 

4017 ---------- 

4018 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

4019 name of column or expression 

4020 offset : int, optional default 1 

4021 number of row to extend 

4022 default : optional 

4023 default value 

4024 

4025 Returns 

4026 ------- 

4027 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

4028 value before current row based on `offset`. 

4029 

4030 Examples 

4031 -------- 

4032 >>> from pyspark.sql import Window 

4033 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([("a", 1), 

4034 ... ("a", 2), 

4035 ... ("a", 3), 

4036 ... ("b", 8), 

4037 ... ("b", 2)], ["c1", "c2"]) 

4038 >>> df.show() 

4039 +---+---+ 

4040 | c1| c2| 

4041 +---+---+ 

4042 | a| 1| 

4043 | a| 2| 

4044 | a| 3| 

4045 | b| 8| 

4046 | b| 2| 

4047 +---+---+ 

4048 >>> w = Window.partitionBy("c1").orderBy("c2") 

4049 >>> df.withColumn("previos_value", lag("c2").over(w)).show() 

4050 +---+---+-------------+ 

4051 | c1| c2|previos_value| 

4052 +---+---+-------------+ 

4053 | a| 1| null| 

4054 | a| 2| 1| 

4055 | a| 3| 2| 

4056 | b| 2| null| 

4057 | b| 8| 2| 

4058 +---+---+-------------+ 

4059 >>> df.withColumn("previos_value", lag("c2", 1, 0).over(w)).show() 

4060 +---+---+-------------+ 

4061 | c1| c2|previos_value| 

4062 +---+---+-------------+ 

4063 | a| 1| 0| 

4064 | a| 2| 1| 

4065 | a| 3| 2| 

4066 | b| 2| 0| 

4067 | b| 8| 2| 

4068 +---+---+-------------+ 

4069 >>> df.withColumn("previos_value", lag("c2", 2, -1).over(w)).show() 

4070 +---+---+-------------+ 

4071 | c1| c2|previos_value| 

4072 +---+---+-------------+ 

4073 | a| 1| -1| 

4074 | a| 2| -1| 

4075 | a| 3| 1| 

4076 | b| 2| -1| 

4077 | b| 8| -1| 

4078 +---+---+-------------+ 

4079 """ 

4080 return _invoke_function("lag", _to_java_column(col), offset, default) 

4081

4083@try_remote_functions 

4084def lead(col: "ColumnOrName", offset: int = 1, default: Optional[Any] = None) -> Column: 

4085 """ 

4086 Window function: returns the value that is `offset` rows after the current row, and 

4087 `default` if there is less than `offset` rows after the current row. For example, 

4088 an `offset` of one will return the next row at any given point in the window partition. 

4089 

4090 This is equivalent to the LEAD function in SQL. 

4091 

4092 .. versionadded:: 1.4.0 

4093 

4094 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

4095 Supports Spark Connect. 

4096 

4097 Parameters 

4098 ---------- 

4099 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

4100 name of column or expression 

4101 offset : int, optional default 1 

4102 number of row to extend 

4103 default : optional 

4104 default value 

4105 

4106 Returns 

4107 ------- 

4108 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

4109 value after current row based on `offset`. 

4110 

4111 Examples 

4112 -------- 

4113 >>> from pyspark.sql import Window 

4114 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([("a", 1), 

4115 ... ("a", 2), 

4116 ... ("a", 3), 

4117 ... ("b", 8), 

4118 ... ("b", 2)], ["c1", "c2"]) 

4119 >>> df.show() 

4120 +---+---+ 

4121 | c1| c2| 

4122 +---+---+ 

4123 | a| 1| 

4124 | a| 2| 

4125 | a| 3| 

4126 | b| 8| 

4127 | b| 2| 

4128 +---+---+ 

4129 >>> w = Window.partitionBy("c1").orderBy("c2") 

4130 >>> df.withColumn("next_value", lead("c2").over(w)).show() 

4131 +---+---+----------+ 

4132 | c1| c2|next_value| 

4133 +---+---+----------+ 

4134 | a| 1| 2| 

4135 | a| 2| 3| 

4136 | a| 3| null| 

4137 | b| 2| 8| 

4138 | b| 8| null| 

4139 +---+---+----------+ 

4140 >>> df.withColumn("next_value", lead("c2", 1, 0).over(w)).show() 

4141 +---+---+----------+ 

4142 | c1| c2|next_value| 

4143 +---+---+----------+ 

4144 | a| 1| 2| 

4145 | a| 2| 3| 

4146 | a| 3| 0| 

4147 | b| 2| 8| 

4148 | b| 8| 0| 

4149 +---+---+----------+ 

4150 >>> df.withColumn("next_value", lead("c2", 2, -1).over(w)).show() 

4151 +---+---+----------+ 

4152 | c1| c2|next_value| 

4153 +---+---+----------+ 

4154 | a| 1| 3| 

4155 | a| 2| -1| 

4156 | a| 3| -1| 

4157 | b| 2| -1| 

4158 | b| 8| -1| 

4159 +---+---+----------+ 

4160 """ 

4161 return _invoke_function("lead", _to_java_column(col), offset, default)

4164@try_remote_functions 

4165def nth_value(col: "ColumnOrName", offset: int, ignoreNulls: Optional[bool] = False) -> Column: 

4166 """ 

4167 Window function: returns the value that is the `offset`\\th row of the window frame 

4168 (counting from 1), and `null` if the size of window frame is less than `offset` rows. 

4169 

4170 It will return the `offset`\\th non-null value it sees when `ignoreNulls` is set to 

4171 true. If all values are null, then null is returned. 

4172 

4173 This is equivalent to the nth_value function in SQL. 

4174 

4175 .. versionadded:: 3.1.0 

4176 

4177 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

4178 Supports Spark Connect. 

4179 

4180 Parameters 

4181 ---------- 

4182 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

4183 name of column or expression 

4184 offset : int 

4185 number of row to use as the value 

4186 ignoreNulls : bool, optional 

4187 indicates the Nth value should skip null in the 

4188 determination of which row to use 

4189 

4190 Returns 

4191 ------- 

4192 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

4193 value of nth row. 

4194 

4195 Examples 

4196 -------- 

4197 >>> from pyspark.sql import Window 

4198 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([("a", 1), 

4199 ... ("a", 2), 

4200 ... ("a", 3), 

4201 ... ("b", 8), 

4202 ... ("b", 2)], ["c1", "c2"]) 

4203 >>> df.show() 

4204 +---+---+ 

4205 | c1| c2| 

4206 +---+---+ 

4207 | a| 1| 

4208 | a| 2| 

4209 | a| 3| 

4210 | b| 8| 

4211 | b| 2| 

4212 +---+---+ 

4213 >>> w = Window.partitionBy("c1").orderBy("c2") 

4214 >>> df.withColumn("nth_value", nth_value("c2", 1).over(w)).show() 

4215 +---+---+---------+ 

4216 | c1| c2|nth_value| 

4217 +---+---+---------+ 

4218 | a| 1| 1| 

4219 | a| 2| 1| 

4220 | a| 3| 1| 

4221 | b| 2| 2| 

4222 | b| 8| 2| 

4223 +---+---+---------+ 

4224 >>> df.withColumn("nth_value", nth_value("c2", 2).over(w)).show() 

4225 +---+---+---------+ 

4226 | c1| c2|nth_value| 

4227 +---+---+---------+ 

4228 | a| 1| null| 

4229 | a| 2| 2| 

4230 | a| 3| 2| 

4231 | b| 2| null| 

4232 | b| 8| 8| 

4233 +---+---+---------+ 

4234 """ 

4235 return _invoke_function("nth_value", _to_java_column(col), offset, ignoreNulls)

4238@try_remote_functions 

4239def ntile(n: int) -> Column: 

4240 """ 

4241 Window function: returns the ntile group id (from 1 to `n` inclusive) 

4242 in an ordered window partition. For example, if `n` is 4, the first 

4243 quarter of the rows will get value 1, the second quarter will get 2, 

4244 the third quarter will get 3, and the last quarter will get 4. 

4245 

4246 This is equivalent to the NTILE function in SQL. 

4247 

4248 .. versionadded:: 1.4.0 

4249 

4250 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

4251 Supports Spark Connect. 

4252 

4253 Parameters 

4254 ---------- 

4255 n : int 

4256 an integer 

4257 

4258 Returns 

4259 ------- 

4260 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

4261 portioned group id. 

4262 

4263 Examples 

4264 -------- 

4265 >>> from pyspark.sql import Window 

4266 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([("a", 1), 

4267 ... ("a", 2), 

4268 ... ("a", 3), 

4269 ... ("b", 8), 

4270 ... ("b", 2)], ["c1", "c2"]) 

4271 >>> df.show() 

4272 +---+---+ 

4273 | c1| c2| 

4274 +---+---+ 

4275 | a| 1| 

4276 | a| 2| 

4277 | a| 3| 

4278 | b| 8| 

4279 | b| 2| 

4280 +---+---+ 

4281 >>> w = Window.partitionBy("c1").orderBy("c2") 

4282 >>> df.withColumn("ntile", ntile(2).over(w)).show() 

4283 +---+---+-----+ 

4284 | c1| c2|ntile| 

4285 +---+---+-----+ 

4286 | a| 1| 1| 

4287 | a| 2| 1| 

4288 | a| 3| 2| 

4289 | b| 2| 1| 

4290 | b| 8| 2| 

4291 +---+---+-----+ 

4292 """ 

4293 return _invoke_function("ntile", int(n))

4387@try_remote_functions 

4388def date_format(date: "ColumnOrName", format: str) -> Column: 

4389 """ 

4390 Converts a date/timestamp/string to a value of string in the format specified by the date 

4391 format given by the second argument. 

4392 

4393 A pattern could be for instance `dd.MM.yyyy` and could return a string like '18.03.1993'. All 

4394 pattern letters of `datetime pattern`_. can be used. 

4395 

4396 .. _datetime pattern: https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/sql-ref-datetime-pattern.html 

4397 

4398 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

4399 

4400 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

4401 Supports Spark Connect. 

4402 

4403 Notes 

4404 ----- 

4405 Whenever possible, use specialized functions like `year`. 

4406 

4407 Parameters 

4408 ---------- 

4409 date : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

4410 input column of values to format. 

4411 format: str 

4412 format to use to represent datetime values. 

4413 

4414 Returns 

4415 ------- 

4416 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

4417 string value representing formatted datetime. 

4418 

4419 Examples 

4420 -------- 

4421 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('2015-04-08',)], ['dt']) 

4422 >>> df.select(date_format('dt', 'MM/dd/yyy').alias('date')).collect() 

4423 [Row(date='04/08/2015')] 

4424 """

4757@try_remote_functions 

4758def date_add(start: "ColumnOrName", days: Union["ColumnOrName", int]) -> Column: 

4759 """ 

4760 Returns the date that is `days` days after `start`. If `days` is a negative value 

4761 then these amount of days will be deducted from `start`. 

4762 

4763 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

4764 

4765 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

4766 Supports Spark Connect. 

4767 

4768 Parameters 

4769 ---------- 

4770 start : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

4771 date column to work on. 

4772 days : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str or int 

4773 how many days after the given date to calculate. 

4774 Accepts negative value as well to calculate backwards in time. 

4775 

4776 Returns 

4777 ------- 

4778 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

4779 a date after/before given number of days. 

4780 

4781 Examples 

4782 -------- 

4783 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('2015-04-08', 2,)], ['dt', 'add']) 

4784 >>> df.select(date_add(df.dt, 1).alias('next_date')).collect() 

4785 [Row(next_date=datetime.date(2015, 4, 9))] 

4786 >>> df.select(date_add(df.dt, df.add.cast('integer')).alias('next_date')).collect() 

4787 [Row(next_date=datetime.date(2015, 4, 10))] 

4788 >>> df.select(date_add('dt', -1).alias('prev_date')).collect() 

4789 [Row(prev_date=datetime.date(2015, 4, 7))] 

4790 """ 

4791 days = lit(days) if isinstance(days, int) else days 

4792 return _invoke_function_over_columns("date_add", start, days)

4902@try_remote_functions 

4903def months_between(date1: "ColumnOrName", date2: "ColumnOrName", roundOff: bool = True) -> Column: 

4904 """ 

4905 Returns number of months between dates date1 and date2. 

4906 If date1 is later than date2, then the result is positive. 

4907 A whole number is returned if both inputs have the same day of month or both are the last day 

4908 of their respective months. Otherwise, the difference is calculated assuming 31 days per month. 

4909 The result is rounded off to 8 digits unless `roundOff` is set to `False`. 

4910 

4911 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

4912 

4913 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

4914 Supports Spark Connect. 

4915 

4916 Parameters 

4917 ---------- 

4918 date1 : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

4919 first date column. 

4920 date2 : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

4921 second date column. 

4922 roundOff : bool, optional 

4923 whether to round (to 8 digits) the final value or not (default: True). 

4924 

4925 Returns 

4926 ------- 

4927 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

4928 number of months between two dates. 

4929 

4930 Examples 

4931 -------- 

4932 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('1997-02-28 10:30:00', '1996-10-30')], ['date1', 'date2']) 

4933 >>> df.select(months_between(df.date1, df.date2).alias('months')).collect() 

4934 [Row(months=3.94959677)] 

4935 >>> df.select(months_between(df.date1, df.date2, False).alias('months')).collect() 

4936 [Row(months=3.9495967741935485)] 

4937 """ 

4938 return _invoke_function( 

4939 "months_between", _to_java_column(date1), _to_java_column(date2), roundOff 

4940 )

4943@try_remote_functions 

4944def to_date(col: "ColumnOrName", format: Optional[str] = None) -> Column: 

4945 """Converts a :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` into :class:`pyspark.sql.types.DateType` 

4946 using the optionally specified format. Specify formats according to `datetime pattern`_. 

4947 By default, it follows casting rules to :class:`pyspark.sql.types.DateType` if the format 

4948 is omitted. Equivalent to ``col.cast("date")``. 

4949 

4950 .. _datetime pattern: https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/sql-ref-datetime-pattern.html 

4951 

4952 .. versionadded:: 2.2.0 

4953 

4954 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

4955 Supports Spark Connect. 

4956 

4957 Parameters 

4958 ---------- 

4959 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

4960 input column of values to convert. 

4961 format: str, optional 

4962 format to use to convert date values. 

4963 

4964 Returns 

4965 ------- 

4966 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

4967 date value as :class:`pyspark.sql.types.DateType` type. 

4968 

4969 Examples 

4970 -------- 

4971 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('1997-02-28 10:30:00',)], ['t']) 

4972 >>> df.select(to_date(df.t).alias('date')).collect() 

4973 [Row(date=datetime.date(1997, 2, 28))] 

4974 

4975 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('1997-02-28 10:30:00',)], ['t']) 

4976 >>> df.select(to_date(df.t, 'yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss').alias('date')).collect() 

4977 [Row(date=datetime.date(1997, 2, 28))] 

4978 """ 

4979 if format is None: 

4980 return _invoke_function_over_columns("to_date", col) 

4981 else: 

4982 return _invoke_function("to_date", _to_java_column(col), format)

4997 """Converts a :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` into :class:`pyspark.sql.types.TimestampType` 

4998 using the optionally specified format. Specify formats according to `datetime pattern`_.

5000 is omitted. Equivalent to ``col.cast("timestamp")``.

5002 .. _datetime pattern: https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/sql-ref-datetime-pattern.html 

5003 

5004 .. versionadded:: 2.2.0 

5005 

5006 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

5007 Supports Spark Connect. 

5008 

5009 Parameters 

5010 ---------- 

5011 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

5012 column values to convert. 

5013 format: str, optional 

5014 format to use to convert timestamp values. 

5015 

5016 Returns 

5017 ------- 

5018 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

5019 timestamp value as :class:`pyspark.sql.types.TimestampType` type. 

5020 

5021 Examples 

5022 -------- 

5023 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('1997-02-28 10:30:00',)], ['t']) 

5024 >>> df.select(to_timestamp(df.t).alias('dt')).collect() 

5025 [Row(dt=datetime.datetime(1997, 2, 28, 10, 30))] 

5026 

5027 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('1997-02-28 10:30:00',)], ['t']) 

5028 >>> df.select(to_timestamp(df.t, 'yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss').alias('dt')).collect() 

5029 [Row(dt=datetime.datetime(1997, 2, 28, 10, 30))] 

5030 """

5032 return _invoke_function_over_columns("to_timestamp", col)

5103 >>> df.select(date_trunc('mon', df.t).alias('month')).collect() 

5104 [Row(month=datetime.datetime(1997, 2, 1, 0, 0))] 

5105 """ 

5106 return _invoke_function("date_trunc", format, _to_java_column(timestamp))

5224

5228

5257@try_remote_functions 

5258def from_utc_timestamp(timestamp: "ColumnOrName", tz: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

5259 """ 

5260 This is a common function for databases supporting TIMESTAMP WITHOUT TIMEZONE. This function 

5261 takes a timestamp which is timezone-agnostic, and interprets it as a timestamp in UTC, and 

5262 renders that timestamp as a timestamp in the given time zone. 

5263 

5264 However, timestamp in Spark represents number of microseconds from the Unix epoch, which is not 

5265 timezone-agnostic. So in Spark this function just shift the timestamp value from UTC timezone to 

5266 the given timezone. 

5267 

5268 This function may return confusing result if the input is a string with timezone, e.g. 

5269 '2018-03-13T06:18:23+00:00'. The reason is that, Spark firstly cast the string to timestamp 

5270 according to the timezone in the string, and finally display the result by converting the 

5271 timestamp to string according to the session local timezone. 

5272 

5273 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

5274 

5275 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

5276 Supports Spark Connect. 

5277 

5278 Parameters 

5279 ---------- 

5280 timestamp : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

5281 the column that contains timestamps 

5282 tz : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

5283 A string detailing the time zone ID that the input should be adjusted to. It should 

5284 be in the format of either region-based zone IDs or zone offsets. Region IDs must 

5285 have the form 'area/city', such as 'America/Los_Angeles'. Zone offsets must be in 

5286 the format '(+|-)HH:mm', for example '-08:00' or '+01:00'. Also 'UTC' and 'Z' are 

5287 supported as aliases of '+00:00'. Other short names are not recommended to use 

5288 because they can be ambiguous. 

5289 

5290 .. versionchanged:: 2.4 

5291 `tz` can take a :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` containing timezone ID strings. 

5292 

5293 Returns 

5294 ------- 

5295 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

5296 timestamp value represented in given timezone. 

5297 

5298 Examples 

5299 -------- 

5300 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('1997-02-28 10:30:00', 'JST')], ['ts', 'tz']) 

5301 >>> df.select(from_utc_timestamp(df.ts, "PST").alias('local_time')).collect() 

5302 [Row(local_time=datetime.datetime(1997, 2, 28, 2, 30))] 

5303 >>> df.select(from_utc_timestamp(df.ts, df.tz).alias('local_time')).collect() 

5304 [Row(local_time=datetime.datetime(1997, 2, 28, 19, 30))] 

5305 """ 

5306 if isinstance(tz, Column): 

5307 tz = _to_java_column(tz) 

5308 return _invoke_function("from_utc_timestamp", _to_java_column(timestamp), tz) 

5309

5311@try_remote_functions 

5312def to_utc_timestamp(timestamp: "ColumnOrName", tz: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

5313 """ 

5314 This is a common function for databases supporting TIMESTAMP WITHOUT TIMEZONE. This function 

5315 takes a timestamp which is timezone-agnostic, and interprets it as a timestamp in the given 

5316 timezone, and renders that timestamp as a timestamp in UTC. 

5317 

5318 However, timestamp in Spark represents number of microseconds from the Unix epoch, which is not 

5319 timezone-agnostic. So in Spark this function just shift the timestamp value from the given 

5320 timezone to UTC timezone. 

5321 

5322 This function may return confusing result if the input is a string with timezone, e.g. 

5323 '2018-03-13T06:18:23+00:00'. The reason is that, Spark firstly cast the string to timestamp 

5324 according to the timezone in the string, and finally display the result by converting the 

5325 timestamp to string according to the session local timezone. 

5326 

5327 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

5328 

5329 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

5330 Supports Spark Connect. 

5331 

5332 Parameters 

5333 ---------- 

5334 timestamp : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

5335 the column that contains timestamps 

5336 tz : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

5337 A string detailing the time zone ID that the input should be adjusted to. It should 

5338 be in the format of either region-based zone IDs or zone offsets. Region IDs must 

5339 have the form 'area/city', such as 'America/Los_Angeles'. Zone offsets must be in 

5340 the format '(+|-)HH:mm', for example '-08:00' or '+01:00'. Also 'UTC' and 'Z' are 

5341 supported as aliases of '+00:00'. Other short names are not recommended to use 

5342 because they can be ambiguous. 

5343 

5344 .. versionchanged:: 2.4.0 

5345 `tz` can take a :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` containing timezone ID strings. 

5346 

5347 Returns 

5348 ------- 

5349 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

5350 timestamp value represented in UTC timezone. 

5351 

5352 Examples 

5353 -------- 

5354 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('1997-02-28 10:30:00', 'JST')], ['ts', 'tz']) 

5355 >>> df.select(to_utc_timestamp(df.ts, "PST").alias('utc_time')).collect() 

5356 [Row(utc_time=datetime.datetime(1997, 2, 28, 18, 30))] 

5357 >>> df.select(to_utc_timestamp(df.ts, df.tz).alias('utc_time')).collect() 

5358 [Row(utc_time=datetime.datetime(1997, 2, 28, 1, 30))] 

5359 """ 

5360 if isinstance(tz, Column): 

5361 tz = _to_java_column(tz) 

5362 return _invoke_function("to_utc_timestamp", _to_java_column(timestamp), tz)

5405 

5406@try_remote_functions 

5407def window( 

5408 timeColumn: "ColumnOrName", 

5409 windowDuration: str, 

5410 slideDuration: Optional[str] = None, 

5411 startTime: Optional[str] = None, 

5412) -> Column: 

5413 """Bucketize rows into one or more time windows given a timestamp specifying column. Window 

5414 starts are inclusive but the window ends are exclusive, e.g. 12:05 will be in the window 

5415 [12:05,12:10) but not in [12:00,12:05). Windows can support microsecond precision. Windows in 

5416 the order of months are not supported. 

5417 

5418 The time column must be of :class:`pyspark.sql.types.TimestampType`. 

5419 

5420 Durations are provided as strings, e.g. '1 second', '1 day 12 hours', '2 minutes'. Valid 

5421 interval strings are 'week', 'day', 'hour', 'minute', 'second', 'millisecond', 'microsecond'. 

5422 If the ``slideDuration`` is not provided, the windows will be tumbling windows. 

5423 

5424 The startTime is the offset with respect to 1970-01-01 00:00:00 UTC with which to start 

5425 window intervals. For example, in order to have hourly tumbling windows that start 15 minutes 

5426 past the hour, e.g. 12:15-13:15, 13:15-14:15... provide `startTime` as `15 minutes`. 

5427 

5428 The output column will be a struct called 'window' by default with the nested columns 'start' 

5429 and 'end', where 'start' and 'end' will be of :class:`pyspark.sql.types.TimestampType`. 

5430 

5431 .. versionadded:: 2.0.0 

5432 

5433 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

5434 Supports Spark Connect. 

5435 

5436 Parameters 

5437 ---------- 

5438 timeColumn : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

5439 The column or the expression to use as the timestamp for windowing by time. 

5440 The time column must be of TimestampType or TimestampNTZType. 

5441 windowDuration : str 

5442 A string specifying the width of the window, e.g. `10 minutes`, 

5443 `1 second`. Check `org.apache.spark.unsafe.types.CalendarInterval` for 

5444 valid duration identifiers. Note that the duration is a fixed length of 

5445 time, and does not vary over time according to a calendar. For example, 

5446 `1 day` always means 86,400,000 milliseconds, not a calendar day. 

5447 slideDuration : str, optional 

5448 A new window will be generated every `slideDuration`. Must be less than 

5449 or equal to the `windowDuration`. Check 

5450 `org.apache.spark.unsafe.types.CalendarInterval` for valid duration 

5451 identifiers. This duration is likewise absolute, and does not vary 

5452 according to a calendar. 

5453 startTime : str, optional 

5454 The offset with respect to 1970-01-01 00:00:00 UTC with which to start 

5455 window intervals. For example, in order to have hourly tumbling windows that 

5456 start 15 minutes past the hour, e.g. 12:15-13:15, 13:15-14:15... provide 

5457 `startTime` as `15 minutes`. 

5458 

5459 Returns 

5460 ------- 

5461 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

5462 the column for computed results. 

5463 

5464 Examples 

5465 -------- 

5466 >>> import datetime 

5467 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame( 

5468 ... [(datetime.datetime(2016, 3, 11, 9, 0, 7), 1)], 

5469 ... ).toDF("date", "val") 

5470 >>> w = df.groupBy(window("date", "5 seconds")).agg(sum("val").alias("sum")) 

5471 >>> w.select(w.window.start.cast("string").alias("start"), 

5472 ... w.window.end.cast("string").alias("end"), "sum").collect() 

5473 [Row(start='2016-03-11 09:00:05', end='2016-03-11 09:00:10', sum=1)] 

5474 """ 

5475 

5476 def check_string_field(field, fieldName): # type: ignore[no-untyped-def] 

5477 if not field or type(field) is not str: 

5478 raise PySparkTypeError( 

5479 error_class="NOT_STR", 

5480 message_parameters={"arg_name": fieldName, "arg_type": type(field).__name__}, 

5481 ) 

5482 

5483 time_col = _to_java_column(timeColumn) 

5484 check_string_field(windowDuration, "windowDuration") 

5485 if slideDuration and startTime: 

5486 check_string_field(slideDuration, "slideDuration") 

5487 check_string_field(startTime, "startTime") 

5488 return _invoke_function("window", time_col, windowDuration, slideDuration, startTime) 

5489 elif slideDuration: 

5490 check_string_field(slideDuration, "slideDuration") 

5491 return _invoke_function("window", time_col, windowDuration, slideDuration) 

5492 elif startTime: 

5493 check_string_field(startTime, "startTime") 

5494 return _invoke_function("window", time_col, windowDuration, windowDuration, startTime) 

5495 else: 

5496 return _invoke_function("window", time_col, windowDuration) 

5497 

5498 

5499@try_remote_functions 

5500def window_time( 

5501 windowColumn: "ColumnOrName", 

5502) -> Column: 

5503 """Computes the event time from a window column. The column window values are produced 

5504 by window aggregating operators and are of type `STRUCT<start: TIMESTAMP, end: TIMESTAMP>` 

5505 where start is inclusive and end is exclusive. The event time of records produced by window 

5506 aggregating operators can be computed as ``window_time(window)`` and are 

5507 ``window.end - lit(1).alias("microsecond")`` (as microsecond is the minimal supported event 

5508 time precision). The window column must be one produced by a window aggregating operator. 

5509 

5510 .. versionadded:: 3.4.0 

5511 

5512 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

5513 Supports Spark Connect. 

5514 

5515 Parameters 

5516 ---------- 

5517 windowColumn : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

5518 The window column of a window aggregate records. 

5519 

5520 Returns 

5521 ------- 

5522 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

5523 the column for computed results. 

5524 

5525 Examples 

5526 -------- 

5527 >>> import datetime 

5528 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame( 

5529 ... [(datetime.datetime(2016, 3, 11, 9, 0, 7), 1)], 

5530 ... ).toDF("date", "val") 

5531 

5532 Group the data into 5 second time windows and aggregate as sum. 

5533 

5534 >>> w = df.groupBy(window("date", "5 seconds")).agg(sum("val").alias("sum")) 

5535 

5536 Extract the window event time using the window_time function. 

5537 

5538 >>> w.select( 

5539 ... w.window.end.cast("string").alias("end"), 

5540 ... window_time(w.window).cast("string").alias("window_time"), 

5541 ... "sum" 

5542 ... ).collect() 

5543 [Row(end='2016-03-11 09:00:10', window_time='2016-03-11 09:00:09.999999', sum=1)] 

5544 """ 

5545 window_col = _to_java_column(windowColumn) 

5546 return _invoke_function("window_time", window_col) 

5547 

5548 

5549@try_remote_functions 

5550def session_window(timeColumn: "ColumnOrName", gapDuration: Union[Column, str]) -> Column: 

5551 """ 

5552 Generates session window given a timestamp specifying column. 

5553 Session window is one of dynamic windows, which means the length of window is varying 

5554 according to the given inputs. The length of session window is defined as "the timestamp 

5555 of latest input of the session + gap duration", so when the new inputs are bound to the 

5556 current session window, the end time of session window can be expanded according to the new 

5557 inputs. 

5558 Windows can support microsecond precision. Windows in the order of months are not supported. 

5559 For a streaming query, you may use the function `current_timestamp` to generate windows on 

5560 processing time. 

5561 gapDuration is provided as strings, e.g. '1 second', '1 day 12 hours', '2 minutes'. Valid 

5562 interval strings are 'week', 'day', 'hour', 'minute', 'second', 'millisecond', 'microsecond'. 

5563 It could also be a Column which can be evaluated to gap duration dynamically based on the 

5564 input row. 

5565 The output column will be a struct called 'session_window' by default with the nested columns 

5566 'start' and 'end', where 'start' and 'end' will be of :class:`pyspark.sql.types.TimestampType`. 

5567 

5568 .. versionadded:: 3.2.0 

5569 

5570 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

5571 Supports Spark Connect. 

5572 

5573 Parameters 

5574 ---------- 

5575 timeColumn : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

5576 The column name or column to use as the timestamp for windowing by time. 

5577 The time column must be of TimestampType or TimestampNTZType. 

5578 gapDuration : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

5579 A Python string literal or column specifying the timeout of the session. It could be 

5580 static value, e.g. `10 minutes`, `1 second`, or an expression/UDF that specifies gap 

5581 duration dynamically based on the input row. 

5582 

5583 Returns 

5584 ------- 

5585 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

5586 the column for computed results. 

5587 

5588 Examples 

5589 -------- 

5590 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([("2016-03-11 09:00:07", 1)]).toDF("date", "val") 

5591 >>> w = df.groupBy(session_window("date", "5 seconds")).agg(sum("val").alias("sum")) 

5592 >>> w.select(w.session_window.start.cast("string").alias("start"), 

5593 ... w.session_window.end.cast("string").alias("end"), "sum").collect() 

5594 [Row(start='2016-03-11 09:00:07', end='2016-03-11 09:00:12', sum=1)] 

5595 >>> w = df.groupBy(session_window("date", lit("5 seconds"))).agg(sum("val").alias("sum")) 

5596 >>> w.select(w.session_window.start.cast("string").alias("start"), 

5597 ... w.session_window.end.cast("string").alias("end"), "sum").collect() 

5598 [Row(start='2016-03-11 09:00:07', end='2016-03-11 09:00:12', sum=1)] 

5599 """ 

5600 

5601 def check_field(field: Union[Column, str], fieldName: str) -> None: 

5602 if field is None or not isinstance(field, (str, Column)): 

5603 raise PySparkTypeError( 

5604 error_class="NOT_COLUMN_OR_STR", 

5605 message_parameters={"arg_name": fieldName, "arg_type": type(field).__name__}, 

5606 ) 

5607 

5608 time_col = _to_java_column(timeColumn) 

5609 check_field(gapDuration, "gapDuration") 

5610 gap_duration = gapDuration if isinstance(gapDuration, str) else _to_java_column(gapDuration) 

5611 return _invoke_function("session_window", time_col, gap_duration)

5617@try_remote_functions 

5618def crc32(col: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

5619 """ 

5620 Calculates the cyclic redundancy check value (CRC32) of a binary column and 

5621 returns the value as a bigint. 

5622 

5623 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

5624 Supports Spark Connect. 

5625 

5626 Parameters 

5627 ---------- 

5628 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

5629 target column to compute on. 

5630 

5631 Returns 

5632 ------- 

5633 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

5634 the column for computed results.

5700@try_remote_functions 

5701def sha2(col: "ColumnOrName", numBits: int) -> Column: 

5702 """Returns the hex string result of SHA-2 family of hash functions (SHA-224, SHA-256, SHA-384, 

5703 and SHA-512). The numBits indicates the desired bit length of the result, which must have a 

5704 value of 224, 256, 384, 512, or 0 (which is equivalent to 256). 

5705 

5706 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

5707 

5708 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

5709 Supports Spark Connect. 

5710 

5711 Parameters 

5712 ---------- 

5713 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

5714 target column to compute on. 

5715 numBits : int 

5716 the desired bit length of the result, which must have a 

5717 value of 224, 256, 384, 512, or 0 (which is equivalent to 256). 

5718 

5719 Returns 

5720 ------- 

5721 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

5722 the column for computed results. 

5723 

5724 Examples 

5725 -------- 

5726 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([["Alice"], ["Bob"]], ["name"]) 

5727 >>> df.withColumn("sha2", sha2(df.name, 256)).show(truncate=False) 

5728 +-----+----------------------------------------------------------------+ 

5729 |name |sha2 | 

5730 +-----+----------------------------------------------------------------+ 

5731 |Alice|3bc51062973c458d5a6f2d8d64a023246354ad7e064b1e4e009ec8a0699a3043| 

5732 |Bob |cd9fb1e148ccd8442e5aa74904cc73bf6fb54d1d54d333bd596aa9bb4bb4e961| 

5733 +-----+----------------------------------------------------------------+ 

5734 """ 

5735 return _invoke_function("sha2", _to_java_column(col), numBits)

5827@try_remote_functions 

5828def assert_true(col: "ColumnOrName", errMsg: Optional[Union[Column, str]] = None) -> Column: 

5829 """ 

5830 Returns `null` if the input column is `true`; throws an exception 

5831 with the provided error message otherwise. 

5832 

5833 .. versionadded:: 3.1.0 

5834 

5835 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

5836 Supports Spark Connect. 

5837 

5838 Parameters 

5839 ---------- 

5840 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

5841 column name or column that represents the input column to test 

5842 errMsg : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str, optional 

5843 A Python string literal or column containing the error message 

5844 

5845 Returns 

5846 ------- 

5847 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

5848 `null` if the input column is `true` otherwise throws an error with specified message. 

5849 

5850 Examples 

5851 -------- 

5852 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(0,1)], ['a', 'b']) 

5853 >>> df.select(assert_true(df.a < df.b).alias('r')).collect() 

5854 [Row(r=None)] 

5855 >>> df.select(assert_true(df.a < df.b, df.a).alias('r')).collect() 

5856 [Row(r=None)] 

5857 >>> df.select(assert_true(df.a < df.b, 'error').alias('r')).collect() 

5858 [Row(r=None)] 

5859 >>> df.select(assert_true(df.a > df.b, 'My error msg').alias('r')).collect() # doctest: +SKIP 

5860 ... 

5861 java.lang.RuntimeException: My error msg 

5862 ... 

5863 """ 

5864 if errMsg is None: 

5865 return _invoke_function_over_columns("assert_true", col) 

5866 if not isinstance(errMsg, (str, Column)): 

5867 raise PySparkTypeError( 

5868 error_class="NOT_COLUMN_OR_STR", 

5869 message_parameters={"arg_name": "errMsg", "arg_type": type(errMsg).__name__}, 

5870 ) 

5871 

5872 errMsg = ( 

5873 _create_column_from_literal(errMsg) if isinstance(errMsg, str) else _to_java_column(errMsg) 

5874 ) 

5875 return _invoke_function("assert_true", _to_java_column(col), errMsg) 

5876 

5877

5914 )

6345 Supports Spark Connect. 

6346 

6347 Parameters 

6348 ---------- 

6349 format : str 

6350 string that can contain embedded format tags and used as result column's value 

6351 cols : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

6352 column names or :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`\\s to be used in formatting 

6353 

6354 Returns 

6355 ------- 

6356 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

6357 the column of formatted results. 

6358 

6359 Examples 

6360 -------- 

6361 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(5, "hello")], ['a', 'b']) 

6362 >>> df.select(format_string('%d %s', df.a, df.b).alias('v')).collect() 

6363 [Row(v='5 hello')] 

6364 """ 

6365 sc = get_active_spark_context() 

6366 return _invoke_function("format_string", format, _to_seq(sc, cols, _to_java_column))

6406@try_remote_functions 

6407def overlay( 

6408 src: "ColumnOrName", 

6409 replace: "ColumnOrName", 

6410 pos: Union["ColumnOrName", int], 

6411 len: Union["ColumnOrName", int] = -1, 

6412) -> Column: 

6413 """ 

6414 Overlay the specified portion of `src` with `replace`, 

6415 starting from byte position `pos` of `src` and proceeding for `len` bytes. 

6416 

6417 .. versionadded:: 3.0.0 

6418 

6419 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

6420 Supports Spark Connect. 

6421 

6422 Parameters 

6423 ---------- 

6424 src : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

6425 column name or column containing the string that will be replaced 

6426 replace : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

6427 column name or column containing the substitution string 

6428 pos : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str or int 

6429 column name, column, or int containing the starting position in src 

6430 len : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str or int, optional 

6431 column name, column, or int containing the number of bytes to replace in src 

6432 string by 'replace' defaults to -1, which represents the length of the 'replace' string 

6433 

6434 Returns 

6435 ------- 

6436 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

6437 string with replaced values. 

6438 

6439 Examples 

6440 -------- 

6441 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([("SPARK_SQL", "CORE")], ("x", "y")) 

6442 >>> df.select(overlay("x", "y", 7).alias("overlayed")).collect() 

6443 [Row(overlayed='SPARK_CORE')] 

6444 >>> df.select(overlay("x", "y", 7, 0).alias("overlayed")).collect() 

6445 [Row(overlayed='SPARK_CORESQL')] 

6446 >>> df.select(overlay("x", "y", 7, 2).alias("overlayed")).collect() 

6447 [Row(overlayed='SPARK_COREL')] 

6448 """ 

6449 if not isinstance(pos, (int, str, Column)): 

6450 raise PySparkTypeError( 

6451 error_class="NOT_COLUMN_OR_INT_OR_STR", 

6452 message_parameters={"arg_name": "pos", "arg_type": type(pos).__name__}, 

6453 ) 

6454 if len is not None and not isinstance(len, (int, str, Column)): 

6455 raise PySparkTypeError( 

6456 error_class="NOT_COLUMN_OR_INT_OR_STR", 

6457 message_parameters={"arg_name": "len", "arg_type": type(len).__name__}, 

6458 ) 

6459 

6460 pos = _create_column_from_literal(pos) if isinstance(pos, int) else _to_java_column(pos) 

6461 len = _create_column_from_literal(len) if isinstance(len, int) else _to_java_column(len) 

6462 

6463 return _invoke_function("overlay", _to_java_column(src), _to_java_column(replace), pos, len) 

6464

6466@try_remote_functions 

6467def sentences( 

6468 string: "ColumnOrName", 

6469 language: Optional["ColumnOrName"] = None, 

6470 country: Optional["ColumnOrName"] = None, 

6471) -> Column: 

6472 """ 

6473 Splits a string into arrays of sentences, where each sentence is an array of words. 

6474 The 'language' and 'country' arguments are optional, and if omitted, the default locale is used. 

6475 

6476 .. versionadded:: 3.2.0 

6477 

6478 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

6479 Supports Spark Connect. 

6480 

6481 Parameters 

6482 ---------- 

6483 string : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

6484 a string to be split 

6485 language : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str, optional 

6486 a language of the locale 

6487 country : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str, optional 

6488 a country of the locale 

6489 

6490 Returns 

6491 ------- 

6492 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

6493 arrays of split sentences. 

6494 

6495 Examples 

6496 -------- 

6497 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([["This is an example sentence."]], ["string"]) 

6498 >>> df.select(sentences(df.string, lit("en"), lit("US"))).show(truncate=False) 

6499 +-----------------------------------+ 

6500 |sentences(string, en, US) | 

6501 +-----------------------------------+ 

6502 |[[This, is, an, example, sentence]]| 

6503 +-----------------------------------+ 

6504 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([["Hello world. How are you?"]], ["s"]) 

6505 >>> df.select(sentences("s")).show(truncate=False) 

6506 +---------------------------------+ 

6507 |sentences(s, , ) | 

6508 +---------------------------------+ 

6509 |[[Hello, world], [How, are, you]]| 

6510 +---------------------------------+ 

6511 """ 

6512 if language is None: 

6513 language = lit("") 

6514 if country is None: 

6515 country = lit("") 

6516 

6517 return _invoke_function_over_columns("sentences", string, language, country)

6559@try_remote_functions 

6560def substring_index(str: "ColumnOrName", delim: str, count: int) -> Column: 

6561 """ 

6562 Returns the substring from string str before count occurrences of the delimiter delim. 

6563 If count is positive, everything the left of the final delimiter (counting from left) is 

6564 returned. If count is negative, every to the right of the final delimiter (counting from the 

6565 right) is returned. substring_index performs a case-sensitive match when searching for delim. 

6566 

6567 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

6568 

6569 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

6570 Supports Spark Connect. 

6571 

6572 Parameters 

6573 ---------- 

6574 str : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

6575 target column to work on. 

6576 delim : str 

6577 delimiter of values. 

6578 count : int 

6579 number of occurences. 

6580 

6581 Returns 

6582 ------- 

6583 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

6584 substring of given value. 

6585 

6586 Examples 

6587 -------- 

6588 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('a.b.c.d',)], ['s']) 

6589 >>> df.select(substring_index(df.s, '.', 2).alias('s')).collect() 

6590 [Row(s='a.b')] 

6591 >>> df.select(substring_index(df.s, '.', -3).alias('s')).collect() 

6592 [Row(s='b.c.d')] 

6593 """ 

6594 return _invoke_function("substring_index", _to_java_column(str), delim, count)

6762@try_remote_functions 

6763def split(str: "ColumnOrName", pattern: str, limit: int = -1) -> Column: 

6764 """ 

6765 Splits str around matches of the given pattern. 

6766 

6767 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

6768 

6769 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

6770 Supports Spark Connect. 

6771 

6772 Parameters 

6773 ---------- 

6774 str : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

6775 a string expression to split 

6776 pattern : str 

6777 a string representing a regular expression. The regex string should be 

6778 a Java regular expression. 

6779 limit : int, optional 

6780 an integer which controls the number of times `pattern` is applied. 

6781 

6782 * ``limit > 0``: The resulting array's length will not be more than `limit`, and the 

6783 resulting array's last entry will contain all input beyond the last 

6784 matched pattern. 

6785 * ``limit <= 0``: `pattern` will be applied as many times as possible, and the resulting 

6786 array can be of any size. 

6787 

6788 .. versionchanged:: 3.0 

6789 `split` now takes an optional `limit` field. If not provided, default limit value is -1. 

6790 

6791 Returns 

6792 ------- 

6793 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

6794 array of separated strings. 

6795 

6796 Examples 

6797 -------- 

6798 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('oneAtwoBthreeC',)], ['s',]) 

6799 >>> df.select(split(df.s, '[ABC]', 2).alias('s')).collect() 

6800 [Row(s=['one', 'twoBthreeC'])] 

6801 >>> df.select(split(df.s, '[ABC]', -1).alias('s')).collect() 

6802 [Row(s=['one', 'two', 'three', ''])] 

6803 """ 

6804 return _invoke_function("split", _to_java_column(str), pattern, limit) 

6805

6807@try_remote_functions 

6808def regexp_extract(str: "ColumnOrName", pattern: str, idx: int) -> Column: 

6809 r"""Extract a specific group matched by a Java regex, from the specified string column. 

6810 If the regex did not match, or the specified group did not match, an empty string is returned. 

6811 

6812 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

6813 

6814 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

6815 Supports Spark Connect. 

6816 

6817 Parameters 

6818 ---------- 

6819 str : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

6820 target column to work on. 

6821 pattern : str 

6822 regex pattern to apply. 

6823 idx : int 

6824 matched group id. 

6825 

6826 Returns 

6827 ------- 

6828 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

6829 matched value specified by `idx` group id. 

6830 

6831 Examples 

6832 -------- 

6833 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('100-200',)], ['str']) 

6834 >>> df.select(regexp_extract('str', r'(\d+)-(\d+)', 1).alias('d')).collect() 

6835 [Row(d='100')] 

6836 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('foo',)], ['str']) 

6837 >>> df.select(regexp_extract('str', r'(\d+)', 1).alias('d')).collect() 

6838 [Row(d='')] 

6839 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('aaaac',)], ['str']) 

6840 >>> df.select(regexp_extract('str', '(a+)(b)?(c)', 2).alias('d')).collect() 

6841 [Row(d='')] 

6842 """ 

6843 return _invoke_function("regexp_extract", _to_java_column(str), pattern, idx)

6846@try_remote_functions 

6847def regexp_replace( 

6848 string: "ColumnOrName", pattern: Union[str, Column], replacement: Union[str, Column] 

6849) -> Column: 

6850 r"""Replace all substrings of the specified string value that match regexp with replacement. 

6851 

6852 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

6853 

6854 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

6855 Supports Spark Connect. 

6856 

6857 Parameters 

6858 ---------- 

6859 string : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

6860 column name or column containing the string value 

6861 pattern : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

6862 column object or str containing the regexp pattern 

6863 replacement : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

6864 column object or str containing the replacement 

6865 

6866 Returns 

6867 ------- 

6868 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

6869 string with all substrings replaced. 

6870 

6871 Examples 

6872 -------- 

6873 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([("100-200", r"(\d+)", "--")], ["str", "pattern", "replacement"]) 

6874 >>> df.select(regexp_replace('str', r'(\d+)', '--').alias('d')).collect() 

6875 [Row(d='-----')] 

6876 >>> df.select(regexp_replace("str", col("pattern"), col("replacement")).alias('d')).collect() 

6877 [Row(d='-----')] 

6878 """ 

6879 if isinstance(pattern, str): 

6880 pattern_col = _create_column_from_literal(pattern) 

6881 else: 

6882 pattern_col = _to_java_column(pattern) 

6883 if isinstance(replacement, str): 

6884 replacement_col = _create_column_from_literal(replacement) 

6885 else: 

6886 replacement_col = _to_java_column(replacement) 

6887 return _invoke_function("regexp_replace", _to_java_column(string), pattern_col, replacement_col)

7120@try_remote_functions 

7121def translate(srcCol: "ColumnOrName", matching: str, replace: str) -> Column: 

7122 """A function translate any character in the `srcCol` by a character in `matching`. 

7123 The characters in `replace` is corresponding to the characters in `matching`. 

7124 Translation will happen whenever any character in the string is matching with the character 

7125 in the `matching`. 

7126 

7127 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

7128 

7129 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

7130 Supports Spark Connect. 

7131 

7132 Parameters 

7133 ---------- 

7134 srcCol : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

7135 Source column or strings 

7136 matching : str 

7137 matching characters. 

7138 replace : str 

7139 characters for replacement. If this is shorter than `matching` string then 

7140 those chars that don't have replacement will be dropped. 

7141 

7142 Returns 

7143 ------- 

7144 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

7145 replaced value. 

7146 

7147 Examples 

7148 -------- 

7149 >>> spark.createDataFrame([('translate',)], ['a']).select(translate('a', "rnlt", "123") \\ 

7150 ... .alias('r')).collect() 

7151 [Row(r='1a2s3ae')] 

7152 """ 

7153 return _invoke_function("translate", _to_java_column(srcCol), matching, replace)

7169@try_remote_functions 

7170def create_map( 

7171 *cols: Union["ColumnOrName", Union[List["ColumnOrName_"], Tuple["ColumnOrName_", ...]]] 

7172) -> Column: 

7173 """Creates a new map column. 

7174 

7175 .. versionadded:: 2.0.0 

7176 

7177 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

7178 Supports Spark Connect. 

7179 

7180 Parameters 

7181 ---------- 

7182 cols : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

7183 column names or :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`\\s that are 

7184 grouped as key-value pairs, e.g. (key1, value1, key2, value2, ...). 

7185 

7186 Examples 

7187 -------- 

7188 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([("Alice", 2), ("Bob", 5)], ("name", "age")) 

7189 >>> df.select(create_map('name', 'age').alias("map")).collect() 

7190 [Row(map={'Alice': 2}), Row(map={'Bob': 5})] 

7191 >>> df.select(create_map([df.name, df.age]).alias("map")).collect() 

7192 [Row(map={'Alice': 2}), Row(map={'Bob': 5})] 

7193 """ 

7194 if len(cols) == 1 and isinstance(cols[0], (list, set)): 

7195 cols = cols[0] # type: ignore[assignment] 

7196 return _invoke_function_over_seq_of_columns("map", cols) # type: ignore[arg-type]

7205 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

7206 Supports Spark Connect. 

7207

7212 col2 : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

7213 name of column containing a set of values 

7214 

7215 Returns 

7216 ------- 

7217 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

7218 a column of map type. 

7219 

7220 Examples 

7221 --------

7229 +----------------+ 

7230 >>> df.printSchema() 

7231 root 

7232 |-- col: map (nullable = true) 

7233 | |-- key: long 

7234 | |-- value: string (valueContainsNull = true) 

7235 """ 

7236 return _invoke_function_over_columns("map_from_arrays", col1, col2)

7352) -> Column: 

7353 """ 

7354 Collection function: returns an array containing all the elements in `x` from index `start`

7356 

7357 .. versionadded:: 2.4.0 

7358 

7359 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

7360 Supports Spark Connect. 

7361

7365 column name or column containing the array to be sliced 

7366 start : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str or int 

7367 column name, column, or int containing the starting index

7369 column name, column, or int containing the length of the slice

7374 a column of array type. Subset of array. 

7375 

7376 Examples 

7377 -------- 

7378 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([([1, 2, 3],), ([4, 5],)], ['x']) 

7379 >>> df.select(slice(df.x, 2, 2).alias("sliced")).collect() 

7380 [Row(sliced=[2, 3]), Row(sliced=[5])] 

7381 """ 

7382 start = lit(start) if isinstance(start, int) else start 

7383 length = lit(length) if isinstance(length, int) else length 

7384 

7385 return _invoke_function_over_columns("slice", x, start, length)

7388@try_remote_functions 

7389def array_join( 

7390 col: "ColumnOrName", delimiter: str, null_replacement: Optional[str] = None 

7391) -> Column: 

7392 """ 

7393 Concatenates the elements of `column` using the `delimiter`. Null values are replaced with 

7394 `null_replacement` if set, otherwise they are ignored. 

7395 

7396 .. versionadded:: 2.4.0 

7397 

7398 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

7399 Supports Spark Connect. 

7400 

7401 Parameters 

7402 ---------- 

7403 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

7404 target column to work on. 

7405 delimiter : str 

7406 delimiter used to concatenate elements 

7407 null_replacement : str, optional 

7408 if set then null values will be replaced by this value 

7409 

7410 Returns 

7411 ------- 

7412 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

7413 a column of string type. Concatenated values. 

7414 

7415 Examples 

7416 -------- 

7417 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(["a", "b", "c"],), (["a", None],)], ['data']) 

7418 >>> df.select(array_join(df.data, ",").alias("joined")).collect() 

7419 [Row(joined='a,b,c'), Row(joined='a')] 

7420 >>> df.select(array_join(df.data, ",", "NULL").alias("joined")).collect() 

7421 [Row(joined='a,b,c'), Row(joined='a,NULL')] 

7422 """ 

7423 get_active_spark_context() 

7424 if null_replacement is None: 

7425 return _invoke_function("array_join", _to_java_column(col), delimiter) 

7426 else: 

7427 return _invoke_function("array_join", _to_java_column(col), delimiter, null_replacement)

7430@try_remote_functions 

7431def concat(*cols: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

7432 """ 

7433 Concatenates multiple input columns together into a single column. 

7434 The function works with strings, numeric, binary and compatible array columns. 

7435 

7436 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

7437 

7438 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

7439 Supports Spark Connect. 

7440 

7441 Parameters 

7442 ----------

7444 target column or columns to work on. 

7445 

7446 Returns 

7447 ------- 

7448 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

7449 concatenated values. Type of the `Column` depends on input columns' type. 

7450 

7451 See Also 

7452 -------- 

7453 :meth:`pyspark.sql.functions.array_join` : to concatenate string columns with delimiter 

7454 

7455 Examples 

7456 -------- 

7457 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([('abcd','123')], ['s', 'd']) 

7458 >>> df = df.select(concat(df.s, df.d).alias('s')) 

7459 >>> df.collect() 

7460 [Row(s='abcd123')] 

7461 >>> df 

7462 DataFrame[s: string] 

7463 

7464 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([([1, 2], [3, 4], [5]), ([1, 2], None, [3])], ['a', 'b', 'c']) 

7465 >>> df = df.select(concat(df.a, df.b, df.c).alias("arr")) 

7466 >>> df.collect() 

7467 [Row(arr=[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]), Row(arr=None)] 

7468 >>> df 

7469 DataFrame[arr: array<bigint>] 

7470 """ 

7471 return _invoke_function_over_seq_of_columns("concat", cols)
