7511@try_remote_functions 

7512def element_at(col: "ColumnOrName", extraction: Any) -> Column: 

7513 """ 

7514 Collection function: Returns element of array at given index in `extraction` if col is array. 

7515 Returns value for the given key in `extraction` if col is map. If position is negative 

7516 then location of the element will start from end, if number is outside the 

7517 array boundaries then None will be returned. 

7518 

7519 .. versionadded:: 2.4.0 

7520 

7521 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

7522 Supports Spark Connect. 

7523 

7524 Parameters 

7525 ---------- 

7526 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

7527 name of column containing array or map 

7528 extraction : 

7529 index to check for in array or key to check for in map 

7530 

7531 Returns 

7532 ------- 

7533 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

7534 value at given position. 

7535 

7536 Notes 

7537 ----- 

7538 The position is not zero based, but 1 based index. 

7539 

7540 See Also 

7541 -------- 

7542 :meth:`get` 

7543 

7544 Examples 

7545 -------- 

7546 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(["a", "b", "c"],)], ['data']) 

7547 >>> df.select(element_at(df.data, 1)).collect() 

7548 [Row(element_at(data, 1)='a')] 

7549 >>> df.select(element_at(df.data, -1)).collect() 

7550 [Row(element_at(data, -1)='c')] 

7551 

7552 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([({"a": 1.0, "b": 2.0},)], ['data']) 

7553 >>> df.select(element_at(df.data, lit("a"))).collect() 

7554 [Row(element_at(data, a)=1.0)] 

7555 """ 

7556 return _invoke_function_over_columns("element_at", col, lit(extraction))

7559@try_remote_functions 

7560def get(col: "ColumnOrName", index: Union["ColumnOrName", int]) -> Column: 

7561 """ 

7562 Collection function: Returns element of array at given (0-based) index. 

7563 If the index points outside of the array boundaries, then this function 

7564 returns NULL. 

7565 

7566 .. versionadded:: 3.4.0 

7567 

7568 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

7569 Supports Spark Connect. 

7570 

7571 Parameters 

7572 ---------- 

7573 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

7574 name of column containing array 

7575 index : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str or int 

7576 index to check for in array 

7577 

7578 Returns 

7579 ------- 

7580 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

7581 value at given position. 

7582 

7583 Notes 

7584 ----- 

7585 The position is not 1 based, but 0 based index. 

7586 

7587 See Also 

7588 -------- 

7589 :meth:`element_at` 

7590 

7591 Examples 

7592 -------- 

7593 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(["a", "b", "c"], 1)], ['data', 'index']) 

7594 >>> df.select(get(df.data, 1)).show() 

7595 +------------+ 

7596 |get(data, 1)| 

7597 +------------+ 

7598 | b| 

7599 +------------+ 

7600 

7601 >>> df.select(get(df.data, -1)).show() 

7602 +-------------+ 

7603 |get(data, -1)| 

7604 +-------------+ 

7605 | null| 

7606 +-------------+ 

7607 

7608 >>> df.select(get(df.data, 3)).show() 

7609 +------------+ 

7610 |get(data, 3)| 

7611 +------------+ 

7612 | null| 

7613 +------------+ 

7614 

7615 >>> df.select(get(df.data, "index")).show() 

7616 +----------------+ 

7617 |get(data, index)| 

7618 +----------------+ 

7619 | b| 

7620 +----------------+ 

7621 

7622 >>> df.select(get(df.data, col("index") - 1)).show() 

7623 +----------------------+ 

7624 |get(data, (index - 1))| 

7625 +----------------------+ 

7626 | a| 

7627 +----------------------+ 

7628 """ 

7629 index = lit(index) if isinstance(index, int) else index 

7630 

7631 return _invoke_function_over_columns("get", col, index)

7694@try_remote_functions 

7695def array_insert(arr: "ColumnOrName", pos: Union["ColumnOrName", int], value: Any) -> Column: 

7696 """ 

7697 Collection function: adds an item into a given array at a specified array index. 

7698 Array indices start at 1, or start from the end if index is negative. 

7699 Index above array size appends the array, or prepends the array if index is negative, 

7700 with 'null' elements. 

7701 

7702 .. versionadded:: 3.4.0 

7703 

7704 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

7705 Supports Spark Connect. 

7706 

7707 Parameters 

7708 ---------- 

7709 arr : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

7710 name of column containing an array 

7711 pos : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str or int 

7712 name of Numeric type column indicating position of insertion 

7713 (starting at index 1, negative position is a start from the back of the array) 

7714 value : 

7715 a literal value, or a :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` expression. 

7716 

7717 Returns 

7718 ------- 

7719 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

7720 an array of values, including the new specified value 

7721 

7722 Examples 

7723 -------- 

7724 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame( 

7725 ... [(['a', 'b', 'c'], 2, 'd'), (['c', 'b', 'a'], -2, 'd')], 

7726 ... ['data', 'pos', 'val'] 

7727 ... ) 

7728 >>> df.select(array_insert(df.data, df.pos.cast('integer'), df.val).alias('data')).collect() 

7729 [Row(data=['a', 'd', 'b', 'c']), Row(data=['c', 'd', 'b', 'a'])] 

7730 >>> df.select(array_insert(df.data, 5, 'hello').alias('data')).collect() 

7731 [Row(data=['a', 'b', 'c', None, 'hello']), Row(data=['c', 'b', 'a', None, 'hello'])] 

7732 """ 

7733 pos = lit(pos) if isinstance(pos, int) else pos 

7734 

7735 return _invoke_function_over_columns("array_insert", arr, pos, lit(value))

7901@try_remote_functions 

7902def explode(col: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

7903 """ 

7904 Returns a new row for each element in the given array or map. 

7905 Uses the default column name `col` for elements in the array and 

7906 `key` and `value` for elements in the map unless specified otherwise. 

7907 

7908 .. versionadded:: 1.4.0 

7909 

7910 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

7911 Supports Spark Connect. 

7912 

7913 Parameters 

7914 ---------- 

7915 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

7916 target column to work on. 

7917 

7918 Returns 

7919 ------- 

7920 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

7921 one row per array item or map key value. 

7922 

7923 See Also 

7924 -------- 

7925 :meth:`pyspark.functions.posexplode` 

7926 :meth:`pyspark.functions.explode_outer` 

7927 :meth:`pyspark.functions.posexplode_outer` 

7928 

7929 Examples 

7930 -------- 

7931 >>> from pyspark.sql import Row 

7932 >>> eDF = spark.createDataFrame([Row(a=1, intlist=[1,2,3], mapfield={"a": "b"})]) 

7933 >>> eDF.select(explode(eDF.intlist).alias("anInt")).collect() 

7934 [Row(anInt=1), Row(anInt=2), Row(anInt=3)] 

7935 

7936 >>> eDF.select(explode(eDF.mapfield).alias("key", "value")).show() 

7937 +---+-----+ 

7938 |key|value| 

7939 +---+-----+ 

7940 | a| b| 

7941 +---+-----+ 

7942 """ 

7943 return _invoke_function_over_columns("explode", col)

7946@try_remote_functions 

7947def posexplode(col: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

7948 """ 

7949 Returns a new row for each element with position in the given array or map. 

7950 Uses the default column name `pos` for position, and `col` for elements in the 

7951 array and `key` and `value` for elements in the map unless specified otherwise. 

7952 

7953 .. versionadded:: 2.1.0 

7954 

7955 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

7956 Supports Spark Connect. 

7957 

7958 Parameters 

7959 ---------- 

7960 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

7961 target column to work on. 

7962 

7963 Returns 

7964 ------- 

7965 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

7966 one row per array item or map key value including positions as a separate column. 

7967 

7968 Examples 

7969 -------- 

7970 >>> from pyspark.sql import Row 

7971 >>> eDF = spark.createDataFrame([Row(a=1, intlist=[1,2,3], mapfield={"a": "b"})]) 

7972 >>> eDF.select(posexplode(eDF.intlist)).collect() 

7973 [Row(pos=0, col=1), Row(pos=1, col=2), Row(pos=2, col=3)] 

7974 

7975 >>> eDF.select(posexplode(eDF.mapfield)).show() 

7976 +---+---+-----+ 

7977 |pos|key|value| 

7978 +---+---+-----+ 

7979 | 0| a| b| 

7980 +---+---+-----+ 

7981 """ 

7982 return _invoke_function_over_columns("posexplode", col)

8024@try_remote_functions 

8025def explode_outer(col: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

8026 """ 

8027 Returns a new row for each element in the given array or map. 

8028 Unlike explode, if the array/map is null or empty then null is produced. 

8029 Uses the default column name `col` for elements in the array and 

8030 `key` and `value` for elements in the map unless specified otherwise. 

8031 

8032 .. versionadded:: 2.3.0 

8033 

8034 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

8035 Supports Spark Connect. 

8036 

8037 Parameters 

8038 ---------- 

8039 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

8040 target column to work on. 

8041 

8042 Returns 

8043 ------- 

8044 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

8045 one row per array item or map key value. 

8046 

8047 Examples 

8048 -------- 

8049 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame( 

8050 ... [(1, ["foo", "bar"], {"x": 1.0}), (2, [], {}), (3, None, None)], 

8051 ... ("id", "an_array", "a_map") 

8052 ... ) 

8053 >>> df.select("id", "an_array", explode_outer("a_map")).show() 

8054 +---+----------+----+-----+ 

8055 | id| an_array| key|value| 

8056 +---+----------+----+-----+ 

8057 | 1|[foo, bar]| x| 1.0| 

8058 | 2| []|null| null| 

8059 | 3| null|null| null| 

8060 +---+----------+----+-----+ 

8061 

8062 >>> df.select("id", "a_map", explode_outer("an_array")).show() 

8063 +---+----------+----+ 

8064 | id| a_map| col| 

8065 +---+----------+----+ 

8066 | 1|{x -> 1.0}| foo| 

8067 | 1|{x -> 1.0}| bar| 

8068 | 2| {}|null| 

8069 | 3| null|null| 

8070 +---+----------+----+ 

8071 """ 

8072 return _invoke_function_over_columns("explode_outer", col) 

8073

8075@try_remote_functions 

8076def posexplode_outer(col: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

8077 """ 

8078 Returns a new row for each element with position in the given array or map. 

8079 Unlike posexplode, if the array/map is null or empty then the row (null, null) is produced. 

8080 Uses the default column name `pos` for position, and `col` for elements in the 

8081 array and `key` and `value` for elements in the map unless specified otherwise. 

8082 

8083 .. versionadded:: 2.3.0 

8084 

8085 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

8086 Supports Spark Connect. 

8087 

8088 Parameters 

8089 ----------

8091 target column to work on. 

8092 

8093 Returns 

8094 ------- 

8095 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

8096 one row per array item or map key value including positions as a separate column. 

8097 

8098 Examples 

8099 -------- 

8100 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame( 

8101 ... [(1, ["foo", "bar"], {"x": 1.0}), (2, [], {}), (3, None, None)], 

8102 ... ("id", "an_array", "a_map") 

8103 ... ) 

8104 >>> df.select("id", "an_array", posexplode_outer("a_map")).show() 

8105 +---+----------+----+----+-----+ 

8106 | id| an_array| pos| key|value| 

8107 +---+----------+----+----+-----+ 

8108 | 1|[foo, bar]| 0| x| 1.0| 

8109 | 2| []|null|null| null| 

8110 | 3| null|null|null| null| 

8111 +---+----------+----+----+-----+ 

8112 >>> df.select("id", "a_map", posexplode_outer("an_array")).show() 

8113 +---+----------+----+----+ 

8114 | id| a_map| pos| col| 

8115 +---+----------+----+----+ 

8116 | 1|{x -> 1.0}| 0| foo| 

8117 | 1|{x -> 1.0}| 1| bar| 

8118 | 2| {}|null|null| 

8119 | 3| null|null|null| 

8120 +---+----------+----+----+ 

8121 """ 

8122 return _invoke_function_over_columns("posexplode_outer", col)

8170@try_remote_functions 

8171def get_json_object(col: "ColumnOrName", path: str) -> Column: 

8172 """ 

8173 Extracts json object from a json string based on json `path` specified, and returns json string 

8174 of the extracted json object. It will return null if the input json string is invalid. 

8175 

8176 .. versionadded:: 1.6.0 

8177 

8178 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

8179 Supports Spark Connect. 

8180 

8181 Parameters 

8182 ---------- 

8183 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

8184 string column in json format 

8185 path : str 

8186 path to the json object to extract 

8187 

8188 Returns 

8189 ------- 

8190 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

8191 string representation of given JSON object value. 

8192 

8193 Examples 

8194 -------- 

8195 >>> data = [("1", '''{"f1": "value1", "f2": "value2"}'''), ("2", '''{"f1": "value12"}''')] 

8196 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("key", "jstring")) 

8197 >>> df.select(df.key, get_json_object(df.jstring, '$.f1').alias("c0"), \\ 

8198 ... get_json_object(df.jstring, '$.f2').alias("c1") ).collect() 

8199 [Row(key='1', c0='value1', c1='value2'), Row(key='2', c0='value12', c1=None)] 

8200 """ 

8201 return _invoke_function("get_json_object", _to_java_column(col), path)

8204@try_remote_functions 

8205def json_tuple(col: "ColumnOrName", *fields: str) -> Column: 

8206 """Creates a new row for a json column according to the given field names. 

8207 

8208 .. versionadded:: 1.6.0 

8209 

8210 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

8211 Supports Spark Connect. 

8212 

8213 Parameters 

8214 ---------- 

8215 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

8216 string column in json format 

8217 fields : str 

8218 a field or fields to extract 

8219 

8220 Returns 

8221 ------- 

8222 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

8223 a new row for each given field value from json object 

8224 

8225 Examples 

8226 -------- 

8227 >>> data = [("1", '''{"f1": "value1", "f2": "value2"}'''), ("2", '''{"f1": "value12"}''')] 

8228 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("key", "jstring")) 

8229 >>> df.select(df.key, json_tuple(df.jstring, 'f1', 'f2')).collect() 

8230 [Row(key='1', c0='value1', c1='value2'), Row(key='2', c0='value12', c1=None)] 

8231 """ 

8232 sc = get_active_spark_context() 

8233 return _invoke_function("json_tuple", _to_java_column(col), _to_seq(sc, fields))

8235 

8236@try_remote_functions 

8237def from_json( 

8238 col: "ColumnOrName", 

8239 schema: Union[ArrayType, StructType, Column, str], 

8240 options: Optional[Dict[str, str]] = None, 

8241) -> Column: 

8242 """ 

8243 Parses a column containing a JSON string into a :class:`MapType` with :class:`StringType` 

8244 as keys type, :class:`StructType` or :class:`ArrayType` with 

8245 the specified schema. Returns `null`, in the case of an unparseable string. 

8246 

8247 .. versionadded:: 2.1.0 

8248 

8249 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

8250 Supports Spark Connect. 

8251 

8252 Parameters 

8253 ---------- 

8254 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

8255 a column or column name in JSON format 

8256 schema : :class:`DataType` or str 

8257 a StructType, ArrayType of StructType or Python string literal with a DDL-formatted string 

8258 to use when parsing the json column 

8259 options : dict, optional 

8260 options to control parsing. accepts the same options as the json datasource. 

8261 See `Data Source Option <https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/sql-data-sources-json.html#data-source-option>`_ 

8262 for the version you use. 

8263 

8264 .. # noqa 

8265 

8266 Returns 

8267 ------- 

8268 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

8269 a new column of complex type from given JSON object. 

8270 

8271 Examples 

8272 -------- 

8273 >>> from pyspark.sql.types import * 

8274 >>> data = [(1, '''{"a": 1}''')] 

8275 >>> schema = StructType([StructField("a", IntegerType())]) 

8276 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("key", "value")) 

8277 >>> df.select(from_json(df.value, schema).alias("json")).collect() 

8278 [Row(json=Row(a=1))] 

8279 >>> df.select(from_json(df.value, "a INT").alias("json")).collect() 

8280 [Row(json=Row(a=1))] 

8281 >>> df.select(from_json(df.value, "MAP<STRING,INT>").alias("json")).collect() 

8282 [Row(json={'a': 1})] 

8283 >>> data = [(1, '''[{"a": 1}]''')] 

8284 >>> schema = ArrayType(StructType([StructField("a", IntegerType())])) 

8285 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("key", "value")) 

8286 >>> df.select(from_json(df.value, schema).alias("json")).collect() 

8287 [Row(json=[Row(a=1)])] 

8288 >>> schema = schema_of_json(lit('''{"a": 0}''')) 

8289 >>> df.select(from_json(df.value, schema).alias("json")).collect() 

8290 [Row(json=Row(a=None))] 

8291 >>> data = [(1, '''[1, 2, 3]''')] 

8292 >>> schema = ArrayType(IntegerType()) 

8293 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("key", "value")) 

8294 >>> df.select(from_json(df.value, schema).alias("json")).collect() 

8295 [Row(json=[1, 2, 3])] 

8296 """ 

8297 

8298 if isinstance(schema, DataType): 

8299 schema = schema.json() 

8300 elif isinstance(schema, Column): 

8301 schema = _to_java_column(schema) 

8302 return _invoke_function("from_json", _to_java_column(col), schema, _options_to_str(options)) 

8303 

8304 

8305@try_remote_functions 

8306def to_json(col: "ColumnOrName", options: Optional[Dict[str, str]] = None) -> Column: 

8307 """ 

8308 Converts a column containing a :class:`StructType`, :class:`ArrayType` or a :class:`MapType` 

8309 into a JSON string. Throws an exception, in the case of an unsupported type. 

8310 

8311 .. versionadded:: 2.1.0 

8312 

8313 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

8314 Supports Spark Connect. 

8315 

8316 Parameters 

8317 ---------- 

8318 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

8319 name of column containing a struct, an array or a map. 

8320 options : dict, optional 

8321 options to control converting. accepts the same options as the JSON datasource. 

8322 See `Data Source Option <https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/sql-data-sources-json.html#data-source-option>`_ 

8323 for the version you use. 

8324 Additionally the function supports the `pretty` option which enables 

8325 pretty JSON generation. 

8326 

8327 .. # noqa 

8328 

8329 Returns 

8330 ------- 

8331 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

8332 JSON object as string column. 

8333 

8334 Examples 

8335 -------- 

8336 >>> from pyspark.sql import Row 

8337 >>> from pyspark.sql.types import * 

8338 >>> data = [(1, Row(age=2, name='Alice'))] 

8339 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("key", "value")) 

8340 >>> df.select(to_json(df.value).alias("json")).collect() 

8341 [Row(json='{"age":2,"name":"Alice"}')] 

8342 >>> data = [(1, [Row(age=2, name='Alice'), Row(age=3, name='Bob')])] 

8343 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("key", "value")) 

8344 >>> df.select(to_json(df.value).alias("json")).collect() 

8345 [Row(json='[{"age":2,"name":"Alice"},{"age":3,"name":"Bob"}]')] 

8346 >>> data = [(1, {"name": "Alice"})] 

8347 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("key", "value")) 

8348 >>> df.select(to_json(df.value).alias("json")).collect() 

8349 [Row(json='{"name":"Alice"}')] 

8350 >>> data = [(1, [{"name": "Alice"}, {"name": "Bob"}])] 

8351 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("key", "value")) 

8352 >>> df.select(to_json(df.value).alias("json")).collect() 

8353 [Row(json='[{"name":"Alice"},{"name":"Bob"}]')] 

8354 >>> data = [(1, ["Alice", "Bob"])] 

8355 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("key", "value")) 

8356 >>> df.select(to_json(df.value).alias("json")).collect() 

8357 [Row(json='["Alice","Bob"]')] 

8358 """ 

8359 

8360 return _invoke_function("to_json", _to_java_column(col), _options_to_str(options))

8363@try_remote_functions 

8364def schema_of_json(json: "ColumnOrName", options: Optional[Dict[str, str]] = None) -> Column: 

8365 """ 

8366 Parses a JSON string and infers its schema in DDL format. 

8367 

8368 .. versionadded:: 2.4.0 

8369 

8370 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

8371 Supports Spark Connect. 

8372 

8373 Parameters 

8374 ---------- 

8375 json : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

8376 a JSON string or a foldable string column containing a JSON string. 

8377 options : dict, optional 

8378 options to control parsing. accepts the same options as the JSON datasource. 

8379 See `Data Source Option <https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/sql-data-sources-json.html#data-source-option>`_ 

8380 for the version you use. 

8381 

8382 .. # noqa 

8383 

8384 .. versionchanged:: 3.0.0 

8385 It accepts `options` parameter to control schema inferring. 

8386 

8387 Returns 

8388 ------- 

8389 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

8390 a string representation of a :class:`StructType` parsed from given JSON. 

8391 

8392 Examples 

8393 -------- 

8394 >>> df = spark.range(1) 

8395 >>> df.select(schema_of_json(lit('{"a": 0}')).alias("json")).collect() 

8396 [Row(json='STRUCT<a: BIGINT>')] 

8397 >>> schema = schema_of_json('{a: 1}', {'allowUnquotedFieldNames':'true'}) 

8398 >>> df.select(schema.alias("json")).collect() 

8399 [Row(json='STRUCT<a: BIGINT>')] 

8400 """ 

8401 if isinstance(json, str): 

8402 col = _create_column_from_literal(json) 

8403 elif isinstance(json, Column): 

8404 col = _to_java_column(json) 

8405 else: 

8406 raise PySparkTypeError( 

8407 error_class="NOT_COLUMN_OR_STR", 

8408 message_parameters={"arg_name": "json", "arg_type": type(json).__name__}, 

8409 ) 

8410 

8411 return _invoke_function("schema_of_json", col, _options_to_str(options))

8587@try_remote_functions 

8588def sort_array(col: "ColumnOrName", asc: bool = True) -> Column: 

8589 """ 

8590 Collection function: sorts the input array in ascending or descending order according 

8591 to the natural ordering of the array elements. Null elements will be placed at the beginning 

8592 of the returned array in ascending order or at the end of the returned array in descending 

8593 order. 

8594 

8595 .. versionadded:: 1.5.0 

8596 

8597 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

8598 Supports Spark Connect. 

8599 

8600 Parameters 

8601 ---------- 

8602 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

8603 name of column or expression 

8604 asc : bool, optional 

8605 whether to sort in ascending or descending order. If `asc` is True (default) 

8606 then ascending and if False then descending. 

8607 

8608 Returns 

8609 ------- 

8610 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

8611 sorted array. 

8612 

8613 Examples 

8614 -------- 

8615 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([([2, 1, None, 3],),([1],),([],)], ['data']) 

8616 >>> df.select(sort_array(df.data).alias('r')).collect() 

8617 [Row(r=[None, 1, 2, 3]), Row(r=[1]), Row(r=[])] 

8618 >>> df.select(sort_array(df.data, asc=False).alias('r')).collect() 

8619 [Row(r=[3, 2, 1, None]), Row(r=[1]), Row(r=[])] 

8620 """ 

8621 return _invoke_function("sort_array", _to_java_column(col), asc)

8623 

8624@try_remote_functions 

8625def array_sort( 

8626 col: "ColumnOrName", comparator: Optional[Callable[[Column, Column], Column]] = None 

8627) -> Column: 

8628 """ 

8629 Collection function: sorts the input array in ascending order. The elements of the input array 

8630 must be orderable. Null elements will be placed at the end of the returned array. 

8631 

8632 .. versionadded:: 2.4.0 

8633 

8634 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

8635 Can take a `comparator` function. 

8636 

8637 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

8638 Supports Spark Connect. 

8639 

8640 Parameters 

8641 ---------- 

8642 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

8643 name of column or expression 

8644 comparator : callable, optional 

8645 A binary ``(Column, Column) -> Column: ...``. 

8646 The comparator will take two 

8647 arguments representing two elements of the array. It returns a negative integer, 0, or a 

8648 positive integer as the first element is less than, equal to, or greater than the second 

8649 element. If the comparator function returns null, the function will fail and raise an error. 

8650 

8651 Returns 

8652 ------- 

8653 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

8654 sorted array. 

8655 

8656 Examples 

8657 -------- 

8658 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([([2, 1, None, 3],),([1],),([],)], ['data']) 

8659 >>> df.select(array_sort(df.data).alias('r')).collect() 

8660 [Row(r=[1, 2, 3, None]), Row(r=[1]), Row(r=[])] 

8661 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(["foo", "foobar", None, "bar"],),(["foo"],),([],)], ['data']) 

8662 >>> df.select(array_sort( 

8663 ... "data", 

8664 ... lambda x, y: when(x.isNull() | y.isNull(), lit(0)).otherwise(length(y) - length(x)) 

8665 ... ).alias("r")).collect() 

8666 [Row(r=['foobar', 'foo', None, 'bar']), Row(r=['foo']), Row(r=[])] 

8667 """ 

8668 if comparator is None: 

8669 return _invoke_function_over_columns("array_sort", col) 

8670 else: 

8671 return _invoke_higher_order_function("ArraySort", [col], [comparator]) 

8672

8765 +------------------------+ 

8766 |data | 

8767 +------------------------+ 

8768 |[[1, 2, 3], [4, 5], [6]]|

8772 +------------------+ 

8773 | r| 

8774 +------------------+

9092@try_remote_functions 

9093def sequence( 

9094 start: "ColumnOrName", stop: "ColumnOrName", step: Optional["ColumnOrName"] = None 

9095) -> Column: 

9096 """ 

9097 Generate a sequence of integers from `start` to `stop`, incrementing by `step`. 

9098 If `step` is not set, incrementing by 1 if `start` is less than or equal to `stop`, 

9099 otherwise -1. 

9100 

9101 .. versionadded:: 2.4.0 

9102 

9103 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

9104 Supports Spark Connect. 

9105 

9106 Parameters 

9107 ---------- 

9108 start : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

9109 starting value (inclusive) 

9110 stop : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

9111 last values (inclusive) 

9112 step : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str, optional 

9113 value to add to current to get next element (default is 1) 

9114 

9115 Returns 

9116 ------- 

9117 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

9118 an array of sequence values 

9119 

9120 Examples 

9121 -------- 

9122 >>> df1 = spark.createDataFrame([(-2, 2)], ('C1', 'C2')) 

9123 >>> df1.select(sequence('C1', 'C2').alias('r')).collect() 

9124 [Row(r=[-2, -1, 0, 1, 2])] 

9125 >>> df2 = spark.createDataFrame([(4, -4, -2)], ('C1', 'C2', 'C3')) 

9126 >>> df2.select(sequence('C1', 'C2', 'C3').alias('r')).collect() 

9127 [Row(r=[4, 2, 0, -2, -4])] 

9128 """ 

9129 if step is None: 

9130 return _invoke_function_over_columns("sequence", start, stop) 

9131 else: 

9132 return _invoke_function_over_columns("sequence", start, stop, step)

9135@try_remote_functions 

9136def from_csv( 

9137 col: "ColumnOrName", 

9138 schema: Union[Column, str], 

9139 options: Optional[Dict[str, str]] = None, 

9140) -> Column: 

9141 """ 

9142 Parses a column containing a CSV string to a row with the specified schema. 

9143 Returns `null`, in the case of an unparseable string. 

9144 

9145 .. versionadded:: 3.0.0 

9146 

9147 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

9148 Supports Spark Connect. 

9149 

9150 Parameters 

9151 ---------- 

9152 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

9153 a column or column name in CSV format 

9154 schema :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

9155 a column, or Python string literal with schema in DDL format, to use when parsing the CSV column. 

9156 options : dict, optional 

9157 options to control parsing. accepts the same options as the CSV datasource. 

9158 See `Data Source Option <https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/sql-data-sources-csv.html#data-source-option>`_ 

9159 for the version you use. 

9160 

9161 .. # noqa 

9162 

9163 Returns 

9164 ------- 

9165 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

9166 a column of parsed CSV values 

9167 

9168 Examples 

9169 -------- 

9170 >>> data = [("1,2,3",)] 

9171 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("value",)) 

9172 >>> df.select(from_csv(df.value, "a INT, b INT, c INT").alias("csv")).collect() 

9173 [Row(csv=Row(a=1, b=2, c=3))] 

9174 >>> value = data[0][0] 

9175 >>> df.select(from_csv(df.value, schema_of_csv(value)).alias("csv")).collect() 

9176 [Row(csv=Row(_c0=1, _c1=2, _c2=3))] 

9177 >>> data = [(" abc",)] 

9178 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ("value",)) 

9179 >>> options = {'ignoreLeadingWhiteSpace': True} 

9180 >>> df.select(from_csv(df.value, "s string", options).alias("csv")).collect() 

9181 [Row(csv=Row(s='abc'))] 

9182 """ 

9183 

9184 get_active_spark_context() 

9185 if isinstance(schema, str): 

9186 schema = _create_column_from_literal(schema) 

9187 elif isinstance(schema, Column): 

9188 schema = _to_java_column(schema) 

9189 else: 

9190 raise PySparkTypeError( 

9191 error_class="NOT_COLUMN_OR_STR", 

9192 message_parameters={"arg_name": "schema", "arg_type": type(schema).__name__}, 

9193 ) 

9194 

9195 return _invoke_function("from_csv", _to_java_column(col), schema, _options_to_str(options)) 

9196 

9197 

9198def _unresolved_named_lambda_variable(*name_parts: Any) -> Column: 

9199 """ 

9200 Create `o.a.s.sql.expressions.UnresolvedNamedLambdaVariable`, 

9201 convert it to o.s.sql.Column and wrap in Python `Column` 

9202 

9203 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

9204 Supports Spark Connect. 

9205 

9206 Parameters 

9207 ---------- 

9208 name_parts : str 

9209 """ 

9210 sc = get_active_spark_context() 

9211 name_parts_seq = _to_seq(sc, name_parts) 

9212 expressions = cast(JVMView, sc._jvm).org.apache.spark.sql.catalyst.expressions 

9213 return Column( 

9214 cast(JVMView, sc._jvm).Column(expressions.UnresolvedNamedLambdaVariable(name_parts_seq)) 

9215 ) 

9216 

9217 

9218def _get_lambda_parameters(f: Callable) -> ValuesView[inspect.Parameter]: 

9219 signature = inspect.signature(f) 

9220 parameters = signature.parameters.values() 

9221 

9222 # We should exclude functions that use 

9223 # variable args and keyword argnames 

9224 # as well as keyword only args 

9225 supported_parameter_types = { 

9226 inspect.Parameter.POSITIONAL_OR_KEYWORD, 

9227 inspect.Parameter.POSITIONAL_ONLY, 

9228 } 

9229 

9230 # Validate that 

9231 # function arity is between 1 and 3 

9232 if not (1 <= len(parameters) <= 3): 

9233 raise PySparkValueError( 

9234 error_class="WRONG_NUM_ARGS_FOR_HIGHER_ORDER_FUNCTION", 

9235 message_parameters={"func_name": f.__name__, "num_args": str(len(parameters))}, 

9236 ) 

9237 

9238 # and all arguments can be used as positional 

9239 if not all(p.kind in supported_parameter_types for p in parameters): 

9240 raise PySparkValueError( 

9241 error_class="UNSUPPORTED_PARAM_TYPE_FOR_HIGHER_ORDER_FUNCTION", 

9242 message_parameters={"func_name": f.__name__}, 

9243 ) 

9244 

9245 return parameters 

9246 

9247 

9248def _create_lambda(f: Callable) -> Callable: 

9249 """ 

9250 Create `o.a.s.sql.expressions.LambdaFunction` corresponding 

9251 to transformation described by f 

9252 

9253 :param f: A Python of one of the following forms: 

9254 - (Column) -> Column: ... 

9255 - (Column, Column) -> Column: ... 

9256 - (Column, Column, Column) -> Column: ... 

9257 """ 

9258 parameters = _get_lambda_parameters(f) 

9259 

9260 sc = get_active_spark_context() 

9261 expressions = cast(JVMView, sc._jvm).org.apache.spark.sql.catalyst.expressions 

9262 

9263 argnames = ["x", "y", "z"] 

9264 args = [ 

9265 _unresolved_named_lambda_variable( 

9266 expressions.UnresolvedNamedLambdaVariable.freshVarName(arg) 

9267 ) 

9268 for arg in argnames[: len(parameters)] 

9269 ] 

9270 

9271 result = f(*args) 

9272 

9273 if not isinstance(result, Column): 

9274 raise PySparkValueError( 

9275 error_class="HIGHER_ORDER_FUNCTION_SHOULD_RETURN_COLUMN", 

9276 message_parameters={"func_name": f.__name__, "return_type": type(result).__name__}, 

9277 ) 

9278 

9279 jexpr = result._jc.expr() 

9280 jargs = _to_seq(sc, [arg._jc.expr() for arg in args]) 

9281 

9282 return expressions.LambdaFunction(jexpr, jargs, False) 

9283 

9284 

9285def _invoke_higher_order_function( 

9286 name: str, 

9287 cols: List["ColumnOrName"], 

9288 funs: List[Callable], 

9289) -> Column: 

9290 """ 

9291 Invokes expression identified by name, 

9292 (relative to ```org.apache.spark.sql.catalyst.expressions``) 

9293 and wraps the result with Column (first Scala one, then Python). 

9294 

9295 :param name: Name of the expression 

9296 :param cols: a list of columns 

9297 :param funs: a list of((*Column) -> Column functions. 

9298 

9299 :return: a Column 

9300 """ 

9301 sc = get_active_spark_context() 

9302 expressions = cast(JVMView, sc._jvm).org.apache.spark.sql.catalyst.expressions 

9303 expr = getattr(expressions, name) 

9304 

9305 jcols = [_to_java_column(col).expr() for col in cols] 

9306 jfuns = [_create_lambda(f) for f in funs] 

9307 

9308 return Column(cast(JVMView, sc._jvm).Column(expr(*jcols + jfuns))) 

9309 

9310 

9311@overload 

9312def transform(col: "ColumnOrName", f: Callable[[Column], Column]) -> Column: 

9313 ... 

9314 

9315 

9316@overload 

9317def transform(col: "ColumnOrName", f: Callable[[Column, Column], Column]) -> Column: 

9318 ... 

9319 

9320 

9321@try_remote_functions 

9322def transform( 

9323 col: "ColumnOrName", 

9324 f: Union[Callable[[Column], Column], Callable[[Column, Column], Column]], 

9325) -> Column: 

9326 """ 

9327 Returns an array of elements after applying a transformation to each element in the input array. 

9328 

9329 .. versionadded:: 3.1.0 

9330 

9331 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

9332 Supports Spark Connect. 

9333 

9334 Parameters 

9335 ---------- 

9336 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

9337 name of column or expression 

9338 f : function 

9339 a function that is applied to each element of the input array. 

9340 Can take one of the following forms: 

9341 

9342 - Unary ``(x: Column) -> Column: ...`` 

9343 - Binary ``(x: Column, i: Column) -> Column...``, where the second argument is 

9344 a 0-based index of the element. 

9345 

9346 and can use methods of :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`, functions defined in 

9347 :py:mod:`pyspark.sql.functions` and Scala ``UserDefinedFunctions``. 

9348 Python ``UserDefinedFunctions`` are not supported 

9349 (`SPARK-27052 <https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-27052>`__). 

9350 

9351 Returns 

9352 ------- 

9353 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

9354 a new array of transformed elements. 

9355 

9356 Examples 

9357 -------- 

9358 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(1, [1, 2, 3, 4])], ("key", "values")) 

9359 >>> df.select(transform("values", lambda x: x * 2).alias("doubled")).show() 

9360 +------------+ 

9361 | doubled| 

9362 +------------+ 

9363 |[2, 4, 6, 8]| 

9364 +------------+ 

9365 

9366 >>> def alternate(x, i): 

9367 ... return when(i % 2 == 0, x).otherwise(-x) 

9368 >>> df.select(transform("values", alternate).alias("alternated")).show() 

9369 +--------------+ 

9370 | alternated| 

9371 +--------------+ 

9372 |[1, -2, 3, -4]| 

9373 +--------------+ 

9374 """ 

9375 return _invoke_higher_order_function("ArrayTransform", [col], [f]) 

9376

9530@try_remote_functions 

9531def aggregate( 

9532 col: "ColumnOrName", 

9533 initialValue: "ColumnOrName", 

9534 merge: Callable[[Column, Column], Column], 

9535 finish: Optional[Callable[[Column], Column]] = None, 

9536) -> Column: 

9537 """ 

9538 Applies a binary operator to an initial state and all elements in the array, 

9539 and reduces this to a single state. The final state is converted into the final result 

9540 by applying a finish function. 

9541 

9542 Both functions can use methods of :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`, functions defined in 

9543 :py:mod:`pyspark.sql.functions` and Scala ``UserDefinedFunctions``. 

9544 Python ``UserDefinedFunctions`` are not supported 

9545 (`SPARK-27052 <https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-27052>`__). 

9546 

9547 .. versionadded:: 3.1.0 

9548 

9549 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

9550 Supports Spark Connect. 

9551 

9552 Parameters 

9553 ---------- 

9554 col : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

9555 name of column or expression 

9556 initialValue : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

9557 initial value. Name of column or expression 

9558 merge : function 

9559 a binary function ``(acc: Column, x: Column) -> Column...`` returning expression 

9560 of the same type as ``zero`` 

9561 finish : function 

9562 an optional unary function ``(x: Column) -> Column: ...`` 

9563 used to convert accumulated value. 

9564 

9565 Returns 

9566 ------- 

9567 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

9568 final value after aggregate function is applied. 

9569 

9570 Examples 

9571 -------- 

9572 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(1, [20.0, 4.0, 2.0, 6.0, 10.0])], ("id", "values")) 

9573 >>> df.select(aggregate("values", lit(0.0), lambda acc, x: acc + x).alias("sum")).show() 

9574 +----+ 

9575 | sum| 

9576 +----+ 

9577 |42.0| 

9578 +----+ 

9579 

9580 >>> def merge(acc, x): 

9581 ... count = acc.count + 1 

9582 ... sum = acc.sum + x 

9583 ... return struct(count.alias("count"), sum.alias("sum")) 

9584 >>> df.select( 

9585 ... aggregate( 

9586 ... "values", 

9587 ... struct(lit(0).alias("count"), lit(0.0).alias("sum")), 

9588 ... merge, 

9589 ... lambda acc: acc.sum / acc.count, 

9590 ... ).alias("mean") 

9591 ... ).show() 

9592 +----+ 

9593 |mean| 

9594 +----+ 

9595 | 8.4| 

9596 +----+ 

9597 """ 

9598 if finish is not None: 

9599 return _invoke_higher_order_function("ArrayAggregate", [col, initialValue], [merge, finish]) 

9600 

9601 else: 

9602 return _invoke_higher_order_function("ArrayAggregate", [col, initialValue], [merge]) 

9603 

9604 

9605@try_remote_functions 

9606def zip_with( 

9607 left: "ColumnOrName", 

9608 right: "ColumnOrName", 

9609 f: Callable[[Column, Column], Column], 

9610) -> Column: 

9611 """ 

9612 Merge two given arrays, element-wise, into a single array using a function. 

9613 If one array is shorter, nulls are appended at the end to match the length of the longer 

9614 array, before applying the function. 

9615 

9616 .. versionadded:: 3.1.0 

9617 

9618 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

9619 Supports Spark Connect. 

9620 

9621 Parameters 

9622 ---------- 

9623 left : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

9624 name of the first column or expression 

9625 right : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

9626 name of the second column or expression 

9627 f : function 

9628 a binary function ``(x1: Column, x2: Column) -> Column...`` 

9629 Can use methods of :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`, functions defined in 

9630 :py:mod:`pyspark.sql.functions` and Scala ``UserDefinedFunctions``. 

9631 Python ``UserDefinedFunctions`` are not supported 

9632 (`SPARK-27052 <https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-27052>`__). 

9633 

9634 Returns 

9635 ------- 

9636 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

9637 array of calculated values derived by applying given function to each pair of arguments. 

9638 

9639 Examples 

9640 -------- 

9641 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(1, [1, 3, 5, 8], [0, 2, 4, 6])], ("id", "xs", "ys")) 

9642 >>> df.select(zip_with("xs", "ys", lambda x, y: x ** y).alias("powers")).show(truncate=False) 

9643 +---------------------------+ 

9644 |powers | 

9645 +---------------------------+ 

9646 |[1.0, 9.0, 625.0, 262144.0]| 

9647 +---------------------------+ 

9648 

9649 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(1, ["foo", "bar"], [1, 2, 3])], ("id", "xs", "ys")) 

9650 >>> df.select(zip_with("xs", "ys", lambda x, y: concat_ws("_", x, y)).alias("xs_ys")).show() 

9651 +-----------------+ 

9652 | xs_ys| 

9653 +-----------------+ 

9654 |[foo_1, bar_2, 3]| 

9655 +-----------------+ 

9656 """ 

9657 return _invoke_higher_order_function("ZipWith", [left, right], [f])

9778@try_remote_functions 

9779def map_zip_with( 

9780 col1: "ColumnOrName", 

9781 col2: "ColumnOrName", 

9782 f: Callable[[Column, Column, Column], Column], 

9783) -> Column: 

9784 """ 

9785 Merge two given maps, key-wise into a single map using a function. 

9786 

9787 .. versionadded:: 3.1.0 

9788 

9789 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

9790 Supports Spark Connect. 

9791 

9792 Parameters 

9793 ---------- 

9794 col1 : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

9795 name of the first column or expression 

9796 col2 : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

9797 name of the second column or expression 

9798 f : function 

9799 a ternary function ``(k: Column, v1: Column, v2: Column) -> Column...`` 

9800 Can use methods of :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`, functions defined in 

9801 :py:mod:`pyspark.sql.functions` and Scala ``UserDefinedFunctions``. 

9802 Python ``UserDefinedFunctions`` are not supported 

9803 (`SPARK-27052 <https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-27052>`__). 

9804 

9805 Returns 

9806 ------- 

9807 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

9808 zipped map where entries are calculated by applying given function to each 

9809 pair of arguments. 

9810 

9811 Examples 

9812 -------- 

9813 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([ 

9814 ... (1, {"IT": 24.0, "SALES": 12.00}, {"IT": 2.0, "SALES": 1.4})], 

9815 ... ("id", "base", "ratio") 

9816 ... ) 

9817 >>> row = df.select(map_zip_with( 

9818 ... "base", "ratio", lambda k, v1, v2: round(v1 * v2, 2)).alias("updated_data") 

9819 ... ).head() 

9820 >>> sorted(row["updated_data"].items()) 

9821 [('IT', 48.0), ('SALES', 16.8)] 

9822 """ 

9823 return _invoke_higher_order_function("MapZipWith", [col1, col2], [f])

9977@try_remote_functions 

9978def bucket(numBuckets: Union[Column, int], col: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

9979 """ 

9980 Partition transform function: A transform for any type that partitions 

9981 by a hash of the input column. 

9982 

9983 .. versionadded:: 3.1.0 

9984 

9985 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

9986 Supports Spark Connect.

9992 ... ).createOrReplace()

9997 target date or timestamp column to work on. 

9998 

9999 Returns 

10000 -------

10002 data partitioned by given columns.

10006 This function can be used only in combination with 

10007 :py:meth:`~pyspark.sql.readwriter.DataFrameWriterV2.partitionedBy` 

10008 method of the `DataFrameWriterV2`. 

10009 

10010 """ 

10011 if not isinstance(numBuckets, (int, Column)): 

10012 raise PySparkTypeError( 

10013 error_class="NOT_COLUMN_OR_INT", 

10014 message_parameters={"arg_name": "numBuckets", "arg_type": type(numBuckets).__name__}, 

10015 ) 

10016 

10017 get_active_spark_context() 

10018 numBuckets = ( 

10019 _create_column_from_literal(numBuckets) 

10020 if isinstance(numBuckets, int) 

10021 else _to_java_column(numBuckets) 

10022 ) 

10023 return _invoke_function("bucket", numBuckets, _to_java_column(col))

10026@try_remote_functions 

10027def call_udf(udfName: str, *cols: "ColumnOrName") -> Column: 

10028 """ 

10029 Call an user-defined function. 

10030 

10031 .. versionadded:: 3.4.0 

10032 

10033 Parameters 

10034 ---------- 

10035 udfName : str 

10036 name of the user defined function (UDF) 

10037 cols : :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` or str 

10038 column names or :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column`\\s to be used in the UDF 

10039 

10040 Returns 

10041 ------- 

10042 :class:`~pyspark.sql.Column` 

10043 result of executed udf. 

10044 

10045 Examples 

10046 -------- 

10047 >>> from pyspark.sql.functions import call_udf, col 

10048 >>> from pyspark.sql.types import IntegerType, StringType 

10049 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(1, "a"),(2, "b"), (3, "c")],["id", "name"]) 

10050 >>> _ = spark.udf.register("intX2", lambda i: i * 2, IntegerType()) 

10051 >>> df.select(call_udf("intX2", "id")).show() 

10052 +---------+ 

10053 |intX2(id)| 

10054 +---------+ 

10055 | 2| 

10056 | 4| 

10057 | 6| 

10058 +---------+ 

10059 >>> _ = spark.udf.register("strX2", lambda s: s * 2, StringType()) 

10060 >>> df.select(call_udf("strX2", col("name"))).show() 

10061 +-----------+ 

10062 |strX2(name)| 

10063 +-----------+ 

10064 | aa| 

10065 | bb| 

10066 | cc| 

10067 +-----------+ 

10068 """ 

10069 sc = get_active_spark_context() 

10070 return _invoke_function("call_udf", udfName, _to_seq(sc, cols, _to_java_column))

10089@overload 

10090def udf( 

10091 f: Callable[..., Any], 

10092 returnType: "DataTypeOrString" = StringType(), 

10093) -> "UserDefinedFunctionLike": 

10094 ... 

10095 

10096 

10097@overload 

10098def udf( 

10099 f: Optional["DataTypeOrString"] = None, 

10100) -> Callable[[Callable[..., Any]], "UserDefinedFunctionLike"]: 

10101 ... 

10102 

10103 

10104@overload 

10105def udf( 

10106 *, 

10107 returnType: "DataTypeOrString" = StringType(), 

10108) -> Callable[[Callable[..., Any]], "UserDefinedFunctionLike"]: 

10109 ... 

10110 

10111 

10112@try_remote_functions 

10113def udf( 

10114 f: Optional[Union[Callable[..., Any], "DataTypeOrString"]] = None, 

10115 returnType: "DataTypeOrString" = StringType(), 

10116) -> Union["UserDefinedFunctionLike", Callable[[Callable[..., Any]], "UserDefinedFunctionLike"]]: 

10117 """Creates a user defined function (UDF). 

10118 

10119 .. versionadded:: 1.3.0 

10120 

10121 .. versionchanged:: 3.4.0 

10122 Supports Spark Connect. 

10123 

10124 Parameters 

10125 ---------- 

10126 f : function 

10127 python function if used as a standalone function 

10128 returnType : :class:`pyspark.sql.types.DataType` or str 

10129 the return type of the user-defined function. The value can be either a 

10130 :class:`pyspark.sql.types.DataType` object or a DDL-formatted type string. 

10131 

10132 Examples 

10133 -------- 

10134 >>> from pyspark.sql.types import IntegerType 

10135 >>> slen = udf(lambda s: len(s), IntegerType()) 

10136 >>> @udf 

10137 ... def to_upper(s): 

10138 ... if s is not None: 

10139 ... return s.upper() 

10140 ... 

10141 >>> @udf(returnType=IntegerType()) 

10142 ... def add_one(x): 

10143 ... if x is not None: 

10144 ... return x + 1 

10145 ... 

10146 >>> df = spark.createDataFrame([(1, "John Doe", 21)], ("id", "name", "age")) 

10147 >>> df.select(slen("name").alias("slen(name)"), to_upper("name"), add_one("age")).show() 

10148 +----------+--------------+------------+ 

10149 |slen(name)|to_upper(name)|add_one(age)| 

10150 +----------+--------------+------------+ 

10151 | 8| JOHN DOE| 22| 

10152 +----------+--------------+------------+ 

10153 

10154 Notes 

10155 ----- 

10156 The user-defined functions are considered deterministic by default. Due to 

10157 optimization, duplicate invocations may be eliminated or the function may even be invoked 

10158 more times than it is present in the query. If your function is not deterministic, call 

10159 `asNondeterministic` on the user defined function. E.g.: 

10160 

10161 >>> from pyspark.sql.types import IntegerType 

10162 >>> import random 

10163 >>> random_udf = udf(lambda: int(random.random() * 100), IntegerType()).asNondeterministic() 

10164 

10165 The user-defined functions do not support conditional expressions or short circuiting 

10166 in boolean expressions and it ends up with being executed all internally. If the functions 

10167 can fail on special rows, the workaround is to incorporate the condition into the functions. 

10168 

10169 The user-defined functions do not take keyword arguments on the calling side. 

10170 """ 

10171 

10172 # The following table shows most of Python data and SQL type conversions in normal UDFs that 

10173 # are not yet visible to the user. Some of behaviors are buggy and might be changed in the near 

10174 # future. The table might have to be eventually documented externally. 

10175 # Please see SPARK-28131's PR to see the codes in order to generate the table below.
